status_message: The leading line of inquiry for the joint investigation is that MH17 was shot down by a Russian BUK missile system. The Netherlands team released a video March 30 showing a Russian flatbed truck carrying a BUK, along with audio of an intercepted phone call between Russian separatists discussing the missiles. The team has appealed for witnesses to come forward.

GM to compensate at least 77 death claims linked to faulty ignition switch
Tesla Motors to announce 'major new product line'

status_message: Rep. Tammy Duckworth (D-IL) announced on March 30 that she will run for U.S. Senate in 2016. Duckworth is looking to unseat Illinois Republican Sen. Mark Kirk. Duckworth, 47, is an Iraq War veteran and was elected to the House in 2012.
link_name: Congresswoman Tammy Duckworth running for Senate
Two federal agents accused of stealing money from the Silk Road

status_message: The National Institutes of Health (NIH) said March 30 that the condition of the healthcare worker infected with Ebola has improved and the worker is now in fair condition. The worker's condition had previously worsened from "serious" to "critical" in mid-March.
link_name: US healthcare worker infected with Ebola now in fair condition

status_message: Apple on March 30 expanded its in-store trade-in program to include select Android and BlackBerry devices. The program lets customers trade in devices for credit toward a new iPhone. Reports of the expanded program first surfaced earlier this month.
link_name: Apple launches Android trade-in program for iPhones
Former JetBlue pilot sues company for $14.9 million after flight diverted
One dead after trying to storm NSA facility in Fort Meade

status_message: The U.S. Supreme Court declined to take up the appeals on March 30 without providing comment. The decision upholds lower court rulings that sided with administrators who established the ban.
link_name: Supreme Court declines to hear case on school banning US flag shirts

status_message: An Australia immigration department employee sent the passport numbers, visa details and other personal information of world leaders to the organizers of the Asian Cup soccer tournament, the Guardian reported March 30. The leaders included U.S. President Barack Obama and Russian President Vladimir Putin.
link_name: Australia accidentally revealed world leaders' personal details at G20 meetings

status_message: Amos Yee, 17, was arrested on March 29 after uploading a video to YouTube celebrating Lee's death and mocking Christianity. In the video, Yee dared Singapore PM Lee Hsien Loong to sue him. At least 20 police reports have been filed against Yee since March 27, the Straits Times reported. The video has been removed and reposted.
link_name: Singapore teen blogger arrested after posting video celebrating ex-leader's death

status_message: Ex-president Nicolas Sarkozy's right-wing UMP party and its allies dominated the second round of local elections on March 29. Based on exit polls, Le Monde reported they won at least 67 departments out of 101 in total, with 28 departments throwing out left-wing parties in favor of the right.
link_name: French conservatives winning local elections, exit polls show

status_message: A crisis in rural India is being fueled by low prices farmers receive, anti-inflation policies, no compensation for income lost to natural disasters, and falling subsidies, Reuters reported March 29. The government says suicides are not linked to storms that damaged about 24.7 million acres of crops.
link_name: India faces rural crisis as Modi shifts focus from subsidies to investment

status_message: GitHub said March 29 that it had been under a DDoS attack for days, but that "we are continuing to adapt and mitigate it." The attack seemed to be focused on two projects: one used by GreatFire, and the other a mirror site for blocked New York Times content for Chinese readers, the Wall Street Journal reported.
link_name: GitHub comes under DDoS attack, Chinese anti-censorship projects targeted

status_message: A court found Olmert guilty of fraud under aggravating circumstances and breach of trust. Olmert accepted bribes from U.S. businessman Morris Talansky in cash-stuffed envelopes containing hundreds of thousands of dollars without reporting it. The charges carry combined maximum sentences of 8 years in prison.
link_name: Former Israeli Prime Minister Olmert guilty in corruption retrial

status_message: Denmark and Australia applied to be founding members of the AIIB, China's Ministry of Finance said March 29. The ministry "welcomed" their decision, the state-run Xinxua news agency reported. The deadline to join the founding of the bank is March 31.
link_name: Australia and Denmark apply to join Asian development bank

status_message: "There's something very dangerous happening in states across the country… These [religious freedom] bills rationalize injustice by pretending to defend something many of us hold dear… This isn't a political issue. It isn't a religious issue. This is about how we treat each other as human beings." - Apple CEO Tim Cook
link_name: Apple's Tim Cook speaks out against religious freedom bills allowing discrimination against gays

status_message: Police said on March 29 that two bodies had been recovered from the rubble at the scene of the building collapse, three days after the explosion at the site. Authorities said the remains had not yet been identified.
link_name: Two bodies recovered from scene of NYC building collapse

status_message: Best Buy announced plans on March 28 to consolidate its Future Shop stores and websites in Canada under the Best Buy brand.
link_name: Best Buy closes Canada's Future Shop outlets

status_message: The highly pathogenic H5N2 strain of avian influenza has infected a third turkey farm in Minnesota, the U.S. Department of Agriculture confirmed on March 28. The latest case was discovered in a commercial flock of 39,000 birds in Stearns County.
link_name: Bird flu outbreak hits Minnesota poultry farms
Nashville DA stops practice of adding sterilization to plea deals

status_message: In response to an increase in new Ebola cases, Guinea's President Alpha Conde on March 28 declared a 45-day "health emergency" that calls for restrictions on movement, shuttering hospitals and clinics where new cases of the virus have been treated and new burial rules.
link_name: Five regions in Guinea under Ebola 'health emergency'

status_message: Thousands lined up in Singapore to pay their respects during the state funeral for Lee on March 29. About 450,000 people, or more than 12% of Singapore's citizens, visited parliament to file past his body by the time a public wake ended March 28, officials said.
link_name: Singapore holds state funeral for 'founding father' Lee Kuan Yew

status_message: A U.S. Dept. of Energy report revealed that a Feb. 2014 radiation leak at the New Mexico's Waste Isolation Pilot Plant was likely due to a reaction from "chemically incompatible" waste, including cat litter, which caused a barrel containing radioactive materials to rupture.
link_name: Cat litter to blame for radiation leak at New Mexico nuclear waste facility
Freddie Mercury biopic starring Sacha Baron Cohen is back on

status_message: Iranian Foreign Minister Mohammad Javad Zarif said March 28 he is confident negotiators will be able to overcome hurdles and reach a deal. Zarif's comments, ahead of the self-imposed March 31 deadline, came after separate meetings with his French and German counterparts.
link_name: Iranian foreign minister confident a nuclear deal will be reached as deadline nears

status_message: Nigerian elections officials said March 28 that voting in some parts of the country had been extended through March 29 due to technical issues with new biometric scanners used for registration.
link_name: Nigeria election extended in some areas due to technical problems
Barbados PM wants to replace Queen of England as island's head of state

status_message: With the Yangtze finless porpoise facing extinction, the Chinese government announced steps to save the species. The plan includes moving some of the critically endangered porpoises out of the polluted Yangtze River and into secure conservation areas with hopes of repopulating the species.
link_name: China sets plan to save critically endangered Yangtze finless porpoise

status_message: Pebble's second Kickstarter campaign ended at 10pm ET on March 27 having raised a total of $20.3 million, which is a new Kickstarter record. A total of 78,471 backers contributed to the campaign.
link_name: Second Pebble Kickstarter concludes, raises $20.3 million

status_message: Amazon will remove non-compete clauses for hourly warehouse workers in the U.S., the company confirmed March 27.

Russian deputy PM says Russia will join Asian development bank

status_message: A Somali UN diplomat and at least 13 other people were killed and dozens injured by the attackers who detonated a car bomb at the hotel entrance before shooting their way inside. Somali special forces eventually killed all six attackers.
link_name: Mogadishu hotel siege ends, at least 20 dead including attackers

status_message: Texas prison officials said March 25 they had acquired enough pentobarbital to carry out out the four executions scheduled for April. Earlier estimates had the state running out in March. The new supply came from an undisclosed compounding pharmacy.

status_message: Reid announced March 27 he would not seek re-election in 2016. He said he contemplated the decision for months and that it was not related to a recent accident while exercising, or the loss of his Senate majority in Nov. 2014 midterm elections.
link_name: Senate Minority Leader Harry Reid will not seek re-election

status_message: The government released a statement on March 26 signed by both frontrunners calling on supporters to "refrain from violence." The pair were renewing a similar pledge made in January before the Feb. 14 elections were postponed due to registration problems and security concerns related to Boko Haram.

status_message: Protests continued in Kabul on March 26 against the killing of Farkhunda, a 27-year-old female religious scholar, a week earlier. A cleric at the protest called on the government to hang the perpetrators "as a lesson for future generations." Further demonstrations are planned.
link_name: Afghans continue protests of killing of female religious scholar

status_message: Arab foreign ministers agreed to a draft resolution to form a unified military force. It could include about 40,000 troops, warships and planes, Egyptian officials told the AP. It would likely be headquartered in Egypt or Saudi Arabia. They will meet again in a month to further discuss the issue.
link_name: Arab League plans to form joint military force

status_message: UN Middle East envoy Robert Serry said March 26: "Illegal settlement activity simply cannot be reconciled with the objective of a negotiated two-state solution and may kill the very possibility of reaching peace on the paradigm of two states for two peoples."
link_name: UN envoy warns Israeli settlements may have killed two-state idea

status_message: At least 20 student activists have had their homes visited by plainclothes police and military officers, Reuters reported March 26, with students saying the visits had occurred in the previous week. A junta spokesman said the visits were part of a policy to discourage protests.
link_name: Thai junta visits homes of student activists, delivers warnings

status_message: North Korea said late March 26 that it had arrested two South Korean nationals sometime in 2014 on spying charges. The men, identified as Choe Chun Gil and Kim Kuk Gi were shown in pictures released by the North at a press conference in Pyongyang.
link_name: North Korea arrests two South Koreans accused of spying

status_message: A number of airlines worldwide said they were immediately changing their rules to require at least two pilots in the cockpit at all times. All U.S. airlines already have the rule in place.

status_message: In a show of bipartisanship, the Republican-controlled Senate voted 61-39 on March 26 to back President Obama's proposal to allow workers to earn up to seven days of paid sick leave. It is unclear if the measure will survive the budget process and become law.

status_message: Pepsi overtook Diet Coke as the second-most popular carbonated soft drink in the U.S. in 2014, according to a March 26 report from the trade publication Beverage Digest. Diet Coke had been second to Coca-Cola since 2010.

status_message: Uber's offices in the Dutch capital of Amsterdam were raided March 26 by transportation regulators. A Dutch court in Dec. 2014 ruled that UberPop, the company's service that relies on private drivers using their own cars, was illegal. Regulators said they were looking for documents showing the size of UberPop.

status_message: WikiLeaks on March 25 released a draft TPP chapter dated Jan. 20. It says no country can treat foreign and local investors differently with policies such as export and supply controls, technology transfer and nationalizations. It would allow foreign firms to sue if they believe a policy harmed their interests.
link_name: Leaked details of Pacific trade deal confirm foreign investors could sue governments

status_message: A French prosecutor said March 26 that the copilot took sole control of the plane while the pilot was locked out of the cockpit. The prosecutor said it was the copilot's "intention to destroy" the plane.
link_name: Officials: Copilot intentionally crashed Germanwings jet

status_message: About 866,000 people sought asylum in 2014, nearly reaching the "all-time high" of almost 900,000 in 1992, a UNHCR report released March 26 said. EU nations received the bulk with 570,800 applications, an increase of 44% from 2013. A fifth of asylum-seekers were Syrians. Iraqis and Afghans were the next largest groups.
link_name: Asylum applications nearly reach 'all-time high' in 2014, UN says

status_message: UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will ask military officials from more than 100 countries to support global peacekeeping efforts during an unprecedented meeting on March 27, the AP reported. His pitch will come following a U.S. call for European nations to step up their contributions.
link_name: UN to ask member states to boost support for troop deployments

status_message: The more than 1,500 Palestinian civilians killed and the estimated 50,000 internally displaced persons in 2014 were the most since war in 1967, the UN said March 26. The death toll was primarily due to the war in Gaza, but also "from policies and practices related to the Israeli occupation."
link_name: UN: Palestinians killed or displaced in 2014 were the most since 1967

status_message: The pronoun "hen" is used to refer to someone without revealing their gender. It was first used in the 1960s but only became widely used in recent years after the transgender community claimed it around 2000. It will join "han" (he) and "hon" (she) in the latest version of the academy's dictionary.
link_name: Official Swedish dictionary to add gender-neutral pronoun

status_message: IOC officials began a 5-day tour of Beijing March 24. On March 25 they toured a suburb of the city where Alpine skiing would be held. Zhang Jiandong, vice-chair of Beijing's bid committee he has "confidence" the city can reduce its notorious pollution before the Games.
link_name: Beijing addresses pollution, Internet access during Olympics bid inspection

status_message: A Chinese foreign ministry spokesperson on March 25 rejected calls from the UN, EU, U.S. and UK to release the women. Two of the women have been transferred to the medical clinics of their detention centers. One of the women claimed she was denied treatment for more than a week in detention, her former lawyer said.
link_name: China rejects calls to release female activists detained for sexual harassment campaign

status_message: Police arrested a suspect on March 26 in Mumbai by tracing his phone's communications tower location. The suspect, Mohammad Selim, was flown back to Kolkata, the capital of West Bengal state, for interrogation. Police hope Selim will lead them to the other men involved.

status_message: Saudi Arabia has deployed a significant task force to its extensive border with Yemen, including an increased tank presence. The Saudis said the move was purely defensive, but it has raised concerns that Yemen will become a power struggle between Sunni Saudi Arabia, and Shiite Iran, which has been accused of backing the Houthi uprising.

status_message: Bergdahl's attorney, Eugene Fidell, told the Washington Post March 25 that his client will be charged with desertion. The move comes ahead of a press conference at 3:30 pm ET where Army officials said they will discuss Bergdhal's case.

status_message: Boeing has been granted a patent for a "force field" with the design name of Method and system for shockwave attenuation via electromagnetic arc. The field, in theory, would activate a protective plasma shield using lasers, electricity and microwaves, after sensing a nearby explosion.

status_message: The BBC announced March 25 that it would not renew Clarkson's contract. The BBC's director general Tony Hall said he had "not taken this decision lightly" but that "a line has been crossed."
link_name: BBC drops Top Gear host Clarkson

status_message: Chan-o-cha on March 25 responded to questions from reporters on how the government would deal with journalists who do not toe the official line. It was unclear if he was joking because he did not smile, Reuters reported. "You don't have to support the government, but you should report the truth," he also said.
link_name: Thai prime minister says he could 'execute' journalists

status_message: An article in the journal Tectonophysics published in March said researchers have found a 120-mile-wide crater in central Australia. The crater is the largest in the world discovered to date. It is actually two craters that probably formed by one meteor that split in two.
link_name: Scientists in Australia find world's largest meteor crater

status_message: Kraft will merge with Heinz, which is owned by Brazilian firm 3G Capital and Warren Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway, the companies announced March 25. The combined company, Kraft Heinz Co., will have an annual revenue of about $28 billion, the companies said.
link_name: Kraft and Heinz merging to form food and beverage giant

status_message: Dai-ichi nuclear plant operator Tokyo Electric Power Co. wasted more than a third of 190 billion yen ($1.6 billion) taxpayer funds for cleanup, according to a Japanese Board of Auditors, the AP reported March 24. The operator used "expensive machines and untested measures that ended in failure" and worked mostly with a single firm.
link_name: Japanese nuclear operator accused of wasting cleanup funds

status_message: Boko Haram militants abducted more than 400 women and girls while fleeing the town of Damasak, Reuters reported March 24, citing residents. At least 70 bodies were also found in a mass grave, some decapitated, military officials said. Troops from Chad and Niger seized the town from Boko Haram on March 21.
link_name: Hundreds believed to have been kidnapped by Boko Haram in northern Nigeria

status_message: Drug-free, non-invasive, ultrasound technology restored memory in 75% of mice treated, research published March 11 in Science showed. The treatment involves rapidly oscillating ultrasound waves that activate microglial cells, which digest and remove the amyloid plaques that destroy brain synapses.
link_name: Australian Alzheimer's treatment restores 75% of lost memory function in mice

status_message: A March 25 China Daily report said that China has sent a "priority list" to U.S. authorities with the names of officials it is seeking for extradition. There are at least 150 Chinese officials living in the U.S. that China suspects of corruption, the report said.
link_name: China sent "priority list" of corrupt officials it wants US to extradite

status_message: A Dept. of Homeland Security investigation found Deputy Sec. Alejandro Mayorkas improperly intervened to help foreign investors obtain visas. The report did not accuse Mayorkas of breaking laws but said his "unprecedented" intervention gave "an appearance of favoritism and special access." The investors had ties to prominent Democrats.
link_name: Report: top DHS official gave special visa treatment to foreign investors tied to Democrats

status_message: South Sudan's parliament voted March 24 to extend both President Kiir's and parliament's terms by three years. Kundu told the AP that the extension was passed to have stability while peace negotiations continued. The country's political opposition denounced the move.
link_name: South Sudan government extends its term by three years

status_message: The average annual number of threats and attacks on Mexican journalists jumped to 328 in the first two years of Enrique Pena Nieto's administration compared to 182 a year during former President Felipe Calderon's term, according to journalism rights group Article 19 March 24.

The company consequently reset all users' passwords as a safety precaution. Twitch did not provide any further details.

status_message: The Commerce Dept. reported March 24 that new home sales rose 7.8% in February, reaching a seven-year high and surprising economic analysts. The figure was 24.8% higher than new home sales in February 2014, and an 87% increase in the northeast alone. The January 2015 rate was revised to 500,000.

status_message: Pompeii's Villa of the Mysteries reopened to visitors after a 900,000-euro ($973,600), two-year restoration, Italian culture minister Dario Franceschini announced March 23. Paintings thought to depict cult of Dionysus rites were excavated in 1748 from the ashes of Mt Vesuvius' 79 A.D. eruption.

status_message: The cat-sized creatures, which weigh about two pounds and are a foot long, detect the presence of tuberculosis bacteria in mucus coughed up from the lower lungs of a patient. Belgian non-profit APOPO also trains giant, pouched, African rats to detect land mines.

status_message: The men convicted of the attacks, Iskandar Ehet, Turgun Tohtunyaz, and Hasayn Muhammad, were executed March 24, a court said.

status_message: High court judge Pablo Ruz found an investigation showed the ruling Popular Party (PP) ran an illegal, secret slush fund for 18 years. The judge recommended a trial for six people, including PP ex-treasurer Luis Barcenas. The judge dropped charges for 22 people.
link_name: Spanish judge recommends trial for ruling party 'slush fund'

status_message: Masked gunmen opened fire on passing vehicles during an early morning attack, local officials said March 24. The gunmen took 13 people off a bus and executed them. No one claimed responsibility. There have been several recent attacks on buses in Afghanistan.

status_message: Israel spied on closed-door nuclear talks with Iran and shared information with U.S. lawmakers, said the Wall Street Journal March 23 citing unnamed sources. The U.S. intercepted Israeli communications with information that only could have come from the talks. An unnamed Israeli official denied the report to the BBC.

status_message: Jolie Pitt wrote in the New York Times March 24 that she opted to have preventative ovarian cancer surgery, which she "had been planning… for some time." Her doctor found "a number of inflammatory markers" were elevated.

status_message: Police on March 23 arrested 79 protesters, including at least one member of parliament, who refused to disperse after they entered a Customs Department office in protest of the GST. At least some of those arrested will be charged with trespassing, police Inspector-General Tan Sri Khalid Abu Baker said.

status_message: Netflix expanded to Australia and New Zealand on March 24. A large number of people there were already believed to be subscribers to Netflix's U.S. service by using VPNs. Reports suggest Netflix's content catalog in Australia initially will be significantly smaller than the U.S. lineup.
link_name: Netflix becomes available in Australia and New Zealand

status_message: India's supreme court ruled on March 24 that a controversial provision in the Information Technology Act allowing police to arrest people who post "offensive" messages online was "unconstitutional and untenable."

status_message: Lawmakers in at least 15 states have introduced bills that would fully or partially exempt video obtained through police body cameras from public records laws.
