status_message: The Supreme Court on March 23 declined to hear a challenge to Wisconsin's voter ID law, a victory for state Republicans who have been pushing for stricter election regulations for voters. Civil rights groups say the law puts a disproportionate burden on poor, elderly and minority voters, who tend to vote for Democrats.
link_name: Supreme Court lets Wisconsin voter ID law stand

status_message: In a March 20 op-ed in Danish newspaper Jyllandposten, Russia reacted to Denmark's decision to join the NATO missile defense shield. Denmark's foreign minister Martin Lidegaard called the statement "unacceptable", adding "Russia knows full well that NATO's missile defense is defensive".
link_name: Russia warns it will target warships if Denmark joins NATO missile shield

status_message: In the first two months of 2015, the government of Haiti reported an average of 1,000 new cases of cholera a week.
link_name: Haiti finds 1,000 new cases of cholera a week in first months of 2015

status_message: Shakhawan Abdullah, a Kurdish lawmaker in Iraq, accused Iran on March 22 of sending 30,000 troops to fight in Iraq under the banner of Shiite militias. Iran has insisted it has only sent military advisers and experts. CIA Director John Brennan said on the same day that Iran was "aggressive and active" in Iraq.
link_name: Kurdish lawmaker accuses Iran of sending thousands of soldiers to Iraq

status_message: Many women and girls displaced by violence and living in camps in Afghan cities are kept in "prison-like" seclusion by male family members, said a report released March 23 by an Afghan-based NGO. They often face hunger and psychological trauma and are denied access to health care and education, it said.
link_name: Displaced women and girls face 'prison-like' conditions in Afghan cities, report says

status_message: Ex-president Nicolas Sarkozy's UMP party and its allies won the first round of local elections on March 22 with 32.5%. The FN placed second with 25.35%, France24 reported, while President Francois Hollande's embattled Socialists came third with 22%. The vote is for representatives of the country's 101 departments.
link_name: Sarkozy's party beats out far-right in local French polls

status_message: Okinawan Gov. Takeshi Onaga ordered Japan's Defense Ministry March 23 to stop survey work at sea for the new base. He said workers may have damaged coral reef by using concrete anchors. Onaga gave the ministry a week to comply. However, Japan's chief cabinet secretary dismissed the order.
link_name: Okinawan governor orders stop to US base relocation survey work

status_message: Up to 40,000 Anti-Austerity Alliance protesters marched through Dublin against additional charges for water. A new water authority will send water bills in early April, which the alliance is urging people to throw away. Water was previously included in bills with other local public services.
link_name: Protesters in Ireland urge people to throw away their water bills

status_message: The federal Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI) took over from the state Criminal Investigation Department on March 22-23. This followed complaints by the National Human Rights Commission and National Commission for Women about why no arrests had been made, despite closed-circuit television (CCTV) evidence.
link_name: Federal investigation begins into gang rape of nun in India

status_message: State-owned ChemChina subsidiary China National Tire & Rubber will first purchase a 26.2% stake in Pirelli owned by Camfin. It will increase that stake to at least 50.1%. The deal was announced March 22. It values Pirelli at $7.7 billion.
link_name: ChemChina to buy controlling stake in Italy's Pirelli

status_message: Cruz formally announced his candidacy on Twitter a little after midnight on March 23. He becomes the first well-known candidate from either party to officially join the 2016 presidential race.
link_name: Ted Cruz announces his run for president in 2016

status_message: In the first game between the two teams from Kansas in 22 years, Wichita State, seeded No. 7, defeated Kansas No. 2 78-65 on March 22. Another No. 7 seed, Michigan St., defeated another No. 2 seed, Virginia, 60-54 to move onto the Sweet 16.
link_name: Michigan St. and Wichita St. both knock off second seeds

status_message: The $54 million made by "Insurgent" over the March 20-22 weekend just missed the $54.6 million "Divergent" made in March 2014. Studio Lionsgate estimated the audience was 60% female for "Insurgent," which also made $47 million in overseas markets in its opening weekend.
link_name: 'Insurgent' takes weekend box office with $54 million

status_message: IMF chief Christine Lagarde said at a conference in Beijing on March 22 that the fund would be "delighted" to cooperate with a new China-led Asian development bank.
link_name: IMF chief Lagarde says there's room for cooperation with Asian development bank

status_message: Lee Kuan Yew died at the age of 91 on March 22 after a long hospitalization for severe pneumonia, the prime minister's office confirmed. Lee served as Singapore's prime minister for 31 years and is credited with transforming Singapore into a thriving economic and global trade center.
link_name: 'Founding father' of Singapore, Lee Kuan Yew, dies at 91

status_message: Starbucks CEO Howard Schultz told employees in a letter that the coffee chain would no longer encourage baristas to write "Race Together" on customers' cups starting March 22.
link_name: 'Race Together' will no longer by written on Starbucks cups

status_message: Hundreds of people lined the streets of Leicester, England, on March 22 for a procession honoring Richard III. Earlier, academics and decedents of the monarch placed white roses on an oak coffin containing his remains. Richard III will be reburied on March 26.
link_name: Ceremony for Richard III held 530 years after death ahead of reburial

status_message: Biotechnology firm Biogen Idec said results from a small clinical trial have shown their experimental drug, aducanumab, can significantly slow the cognitive decline in patients who have suffered only mild symptoms of Alzheimer's or who are in the early stages of the disease.
link_name: Experimental drug slows cognitive decline, offers hope for Alzheimer's sufferers

status_message: A Manhattan federal judge, March 20, approved a $970.5 million settlement to a class-action lawsuit brought by AIG shareholders who said they were misled over the insurance firm's exposure to subprime mortgages. Its the largest settlement to a case where no criminal or regulatory charges were brought.
link_name: Shareholders to receive $970M from AIG over subprime mortgages

status_message: Six men were arrested after attacking a synagogue in north London in the early morning of March 22. The men were described as drunk after leaving a nearby party. A video posted to YouTube showed the men smashing windows and forcing the doors of the synagogue.
link_name: 6 arrested after anti-Semitic confrontation at London synagogue

status_message: A high tide estimated at some 50 feet completely covered the footbridge connecting Mont Saint-Michel to the mainland on March 21. The supertide actually happens around the same time every 18 years. It's not expected to occur again until 2033.
link_name: Mont Saint-Michel cut off by 'tide of the century'

status_message: Legislation proposed March 19 in North Carolina would remove the religious exemption that currently allows parents not to vaccinate their children if it's against their beliefs. Parents can skip childhood vaccination due to personal beliefs in 20 states, including California.
link_name: North Carolina bill would mandate vaccinations for kids attending school
Suspect in New Orleans airport attack dies in hospital

status_message: A proposed stadium to be used by the NFL's Chargers and Raiders in Carson, Calif., cleared an early hurdle March 21 after organizers said they collected 14,000 signatures to put the it on the ballot for city voters.
link_name: Proposed NFL stadium in Los Angeles clears early hurdle
WHO agency: Monsanto weedkiller is 'probably carcinogenic'

status_message: Several reports March 21, citing unnamed Yemeni military sources, said U.S. forces had evacuated the Al-Anad airbase a day after Al-Qaeda fighters stormed the nearby city of Al-Houta. About 100 U.S. troops are thought to be stationed at the base where they assist with training and logistical support in the battle against extremists in the region.
link_name: Reports: US military pulls out of Yemen due to increasing insecurity

status_message: Steve Nash announced his retirement from the NBA in a March 21 letter published on the Players' Tribune website. Nash played 19 seasons, racking up the third-most assists in league history and earning two MVP honors.
link_name: Steve Nash, 2-time NBA MVP, announces retirement

status_message: Former FBI agent, Matthew Lowry, was charged March 20 with 64 criminal offenses for allegedly stealing heroin from the agency's evidence facility in Washington, DC. The former agent is accused of using the stolen heroin himself.
link_name: Former FBI agent charged with stealing, using heroin evidence

status_message: On March 23, Paris officials will aim to stop one in every two cars from entering Paris streets, allowing only vehicles with license plates ending in odd numbers. All public transportation will also be free in the city and surrounding areas in a bid to lower pollution levels by encouraging drivers to seek alternatives.
link_name: Paris enacts emergency transportation measures due to smog

status_message: A fire that engulfed a Brooklyn home took the lives of seven children between the ages of 5 and 15. The mother of the children and one of her daughters survived the blaze by jumping from second floor windows. Authorities said fire was likely started by a faulty hot plate.
link_name: Fire kills 7 children from same family in Brooklyn
57 dogs and puppies rescued from South Korean meat farm brought to CA

status_message: Steven Lloyd Sadler, known on the Silk Road as "NOD," was sentenced on March 19 to five years in prison and an additional four years of supervised release. Sadler, 40, from Bellevue, Wash., shipped nearly $1 million in illegal drugs through the mail to his customers on the Silk Road.
link_name: Top 'Silk Road' vendor sentenced to 5 years in prison

status_message: The foreign ministers of China and Japan met in Seoul with South Korea's foreign minister March 21, the first such trilateral meeting between the countries since 2012.
link_name: Japan, China and South Korea hold diplomatic talks
Rosetta finds first molecular nitrogen on a comet

status_message: In a report released March 19, Denver's auditor said the city jail is "seriously mismanaged" and blamed Sheriff's Dept. officials for putting "inmates, detainees, deputies and taxpayers at significant risk."
link_name: Denver auditor says jail facing abuse claims is 'seriously mismanaged'
San Francisco ranks highest in LGBT percentage, Birmingham ranks lowest
FDA approves new GMO apples and potatoes for consumption
Dow stocks end week up nearly 1% on weaker US dollar
White House names first 'director of information technology'
FBI launches preliminary investigation against Schock following ethics scandal
2 found guilty in Canadian train terror plot
Former rap mogul Suge Knight collapses after bail hearing
Hanging death of black Mississippi man spurs FBI investigation
World may see 40% water supply shortfall in just 15 years, UN says

status_message: The BBC said March 19 that it will provide a report next week into an incident between "Top Gear" host Jeremy Clarkson and producer Oisin Tymon that occurred two weeks ago. Jeremy Clarkson was suspended March 10 "pending an investigation," the BBC said.
link_name: BBC to provide report on Top Gear 'fracas' involving host Jeremy Clarkson next week
Gov't agencies look to curtail use of 'lost pleasure' analysis in public health
Tinder appoints former eBay executive Chris Payne as CEO
IRS to work with TurboTax maker, states to combat fraud
NYPD commissioner proposes unit to investigate police-involved shootings
Report: 'Overhauled' Apple TV to debut this summer

status_message: The Great Barrier Reef faces an "unfolding disaster," research published on March 20 by the Science journal shows. It faces threats of climate change exacerbating local problems of overfishing, chemical pollution from agriculture and dredging seabeds to facilitate port expansions on the Great Barrier Reef.
link_name: Great Barrier Reef faces 'disaster,' researchers say

status_message: The 2015 UK budget provided support for the world's largest, contiguous marine ocean reserve. The islands are administered by the UK. Fishing and seabed mining are prohibited in the 322,000-square-mile (830,000-square-kilometer) marine reserve. The area will be monitored using real-time satellites.
link_name: UK budgets for world's largest ocean reserve in the Pacific

status_message: A website by Syrian activists posted a photo of an IS commander known as Abu Wahib, saying he looked like a shawerma skewer. Satirists have also made fun of him to show him in a shampoo commercial and on a dating website. The well-known commander was held in a U.S.-run Iraqi prison before he was moved and escaped in a prison break.
link_name: Syrian activists skewer Islamic State commander photos

status_message: Internal WHO emails show that the organization's leadership put off declaring Ebola an international emergency for at least two months starting in June 2014, the AP said March 20. Among the rationales used in the emails was that a declaration "could be seen as a hostile act" to some West African nations.
link_name: Report: WHO held off declaring Ebola an international emergency

status_message: 67-year-old Opas Charnsuksai was sentenced to a year and a half in prison on March 20 for writing messages in a shopping mall toilet stall that "lowered the value of the king." Although most of what he wrote was critical of Thai coup leader Prayuth Chan-o-cha, one line referred to the king.
link_name: Elderly Thai man convicted for anti-royal graffiti

status_message: Secret Service Director Joseph Clancy told a Senate panel March 19 that the agency was working to recover security footage from the night in question. The video was automatically recorded over, which happens with all security video after 72 hours. The allegation that the agents were drunk is still under investigation.
link_name: Secret Service chief denies crash happened at White House

status_message: An assessment of wild bee species in Europe released March 19 found more than 9% are threatened with extinction, with another 5% are likely to be threatened soon. The study said the loss and degradation of bee habitats, usually due to agricultural practices, is their primary threat.
link_name: Study: Nearly 1 in 10 wild bee species in Europe face extinction

status_message: Reuters reported March 20 that both the Chinese and English version of its website was blocked in China. Circa confirmed that the website is currently blocked. The country's Internet regulator did not respond to a request for comment. Thomson Reuters' financial news and data services remained functional for its clients.
link_name: Reuters website blocked in China
Monica Lewinsky delivers TED Talk to discuss mistakes, cyberbullying
Lawmakers seek to end publicly funded first-class flights for Congress
Florida governor stops using state email after private email controversy
House votes to strike rule that speeds up unionizing workers
Grocery delivery startup Instacart hit with employment status lawsuit
FAA grants Amazon permission to test drones
Baylor, Iowa State suffer big early March Madness upsets
Victim of 9/11 World Trade Center attacks identified 13 years later
Report: FTC staff wanted to sue Google over anticompetitive tactics
Amazon brings one-hour delivery to Baltimore, Miami
2015 'State of Black America' report shows rise in social justice for blacks
Report: White House to unveil federal-land fracking rules
Lawmakers introduce bill to televise Supreme Court arguments
Angry Birds maker Rovio sees 9% drop in revenue in 2014
Obama orders 40% cut in federal greenhouse gas emissions
FIFA announces 2022 World Cup final to be held on Dec. 18

status_message: Tesla Motors said March 19 that it will soon send an over-the-air update for the Model S that will automatically alert drivers before they drive out of the range of a charger.
link_name: Tesla Model S software update to alert drivers of maximum range
Body of missing Wall Street Journal reporter found in New Jersey river
Poll: 69% of voters support LGBT workplace protections
After 60 years, Switzerland lifts motor racing ban for Formula E
Islamic State recording claims responsibility for deadly Tunisia museum attack
Tag Heuer developing 'luxury' Android Wear smartwatch
Report: CA governor wants $1 billion for drought relief
Google patents disease-fighting wristband technology
Serbian police arrest 7 in connection to 1995 massacre of Bosniaks

status_message: Chinese Assistant Foreign Minister Liu Jianchao and other officials visited Tokyo March 19 to hold the first high-level security talks with Japan since 2011. "The best way to dissolve concerns is to hold direct dialogue," said Shinsuke Sugiyama, Liu's Japanese counterpart. Talks on March 21 will include South Korea.
link_name: Japan and China hold first security talks since 2011

status_message: Joseph Roche, one of 100 finalists selected by Mars One in 2014, wrote an op-ed on Mars One in The Guardian March 18. He says the venture is "ambitious but naive and unrealistic." He claims a the ranking of the 100 finalists is solely based on how much financial support they gave, which Mars One denies.
link_name: Mars One finalist: project is "naive and unrealistic"

status_message: China will add 200,000 alternative fuel public buses and 100,000 alternative fuel taxis by 2020, China's Transport Ministry said March 18, according to the AP.
link_name: China will add hundreds of thousands of alternative fuel buses and taxis by 2020

status_message: Switzerland froze assets worth $400 million on March 18 as multiple investigations into money laundering widened. Bern-based federal prosecutors said in a March 18 statement that the frozen assets were identified in more than 300 accounts in 30 banks and were used for bribery in Brazil.
link_name: Switzerland freezes $400 million after accusations of bribery in Brazil

status_message: Chinese television station Hunan TV announced March 18 that it will invest $1.5 billion to co-produce 50 films by Hollywood studio Lionsgate. The partnership also gives Hunan TV the option to distribute four of Lionsgate's films annually, according to Chinese state media.
link_name: Chinese TV channel signs $1.5 billion co-production deal with Lionsgate

status_message: Myanmar Post Journal Chief Editor Than Htike Thu and Deputy Chief Reporter Hsan Moe Tun were jailed for two months on March 18 for defamation. Since 2011, 10 journalists in Myanmar have been jailed and another 19 are facing trial, the Committee to Protect Journalists says.
link_name: Myanmar jails two journalists for defamation

status_message: New home prices fell 5.7% year-on-year in February, setting a record for the largest decline for a second straight month, China's National Bureau of Statistics said March 18. Sixty-six of the 70 major cities that are tracked saw month-to-month declines from January to February.
link_name: Chinese home prices fall by record for second straight month

status_message: U.S. personnel and surveillance were part of the failed raid, a Philippine Senate investigation released March 17 said. At least 6 Americans were at the Philippine command post during the raid. The U.S. previously said it only helped evacuate injured Philippine troops. The State Dept. and Pentagon declined to confirm the report.
link_name: US played role in botched commando raid in the Philippines

status_message: China named Li Jinjun, 59, as its new ambassador to North Korea March 18. Li was previously China's ambassador to the Philippines and Myanmar.
link_name: China appoints new ambassador to North Korea

status_message: According to a UN report released March 16, 88% of the people affected by natural disasters worldwide from 1970-2014 lived in Asia and Pacific. More than 2 million people in the region were killed by natural disasters in 45 years, accounting for more that 56% of disaster-related deaths worldwide.
link_name: UN: 88% of people most affected by natural disasters live in Asia and the Pacific

status_message: The Supreme Court decided on March 19 to proceed to trial for Yingluck, who faces a maximum of 10 years in prison. Thailand's military-appointed attorney general filed three charges with the Supreme Court Feb. 19, including an anti-corruption charge and two counts of negligence.
link_name: Ousted Thai premier to face trial for corruption and negligence charges
Target will pay $10 million to data breach victims in proposed settlement
Pentagon loses track of weapons, equipment given to Yemen
First direct charter flights from New York to Cuba take off
Police describe shootout with Tsarnaev brothers, Tamerlan's death
Presenters for Rock and Roll Hall of Fame class of 2015 announced
Target to increase minimum wage to $9 per hour
'Dark Web' marketplace Evolution vanishes, up to $38M believed stolen

status_message: The California Franchise Tax Board stripped Blue Shield of California of its state tax-exempt status without a formal announcement on August 28, 2014 but confirmed its action on March 17. Blue Shield, California's third largest health insurer, is protesting the state's decision but could owe tens of millions in state taxes if the appeal fails.
link_name: Blue Shield of California has tax-exempt status revoked

status_message: A Paris court on March 18 handed Dieudonne M'bala M'bala a suspended two-month jail sentence for condoning terrorism. Prosecutors sought $32,000, or 200 days of jail time if Dieudonne failed to pay. His lawyers plan on appealing the charge.
link_name: Dieudonne served two months suspended jail sentence for being an 'apologist for terrorism'

status_message: New Jersey Gov. Chris Christie on March 18 signed a bill into law that allows Tesla Motors to sell its cars directly to consumers in the state. Gov. Christie signed the bill into law two days after the New Jersey Senate passed it. The state Assembly passed the bill in June 2014.
link_name: New Jersey now allows direct Tesla sales to consumers

status_message:
US music streaming revenue rises 29% to $1.9 billion in 2014

Download revenue down 7.1% 

Vinyl revenue up 49%
link_name: US music streaming revenue rises 29% to $1.9 billion in 2014, download revenue down 7.1%

status_message: In its March 18 statement, the Federal Open Market Committee dropped the language that it would remain "patient" in raising the base interest rate. It said the current 0-0.25% range "remains appropriate" and that it would be unlikely to change that at its April meeting. The Fed will consider to monitor improvements in the labor force and inflation conditions before raising the rate.
link_name: Fed drops 'patience' language from statement, indicating future rate hikes

status_message: Russian and South Korean scientists, March 16, began the process of retrieving DNA from the bone marrow from a well-preserved woolly mammoth leg. The team hopes to collect enough high-quality samples to construct a full mammoth genome within one to two years. The hope is that it could be implanted in an elephant embryo, creating a mammoth clone.
link_name: Scientists attempt DNA extraction from mammoth carcass for cloning project

status_message: A report released by Human Rights Watch on March 18 found the Iraqi military and militias looted and razed the property of civilians who fled fighting. They destroyed at least two villages. The report was based on documents, photos and video, interviews and satellite images. It also documented the abduction of 11 men.
link_name: Iraqi military, militias accused of looting and razing homes

status_message: On March 14 Oregon Gov. Kate Brown (D) signed new legislation that will make Oregon the first state in the nation to adopt automatic voter registration. With the new law, any unregistered adult Oregon citizen who has interacted with the state's Motor Vehicle Services Division since 2013 will be mailed a ballot 20 days before the next statewide election.
link_name: Oregon becomes first state to implement automatic voter registration

status_message: The lawsuit, brought by four detainees at Abu Ghraib prison between 2003 and 2008, targets prison operator CACI Premier Technology. The company attempted to file a motion to dismiss the case in 2009, but lost the appeal in June 2014. The case subsequently heard oral arguments on Feb. 6.
link_name: US contractor could face Abu Ghraib suit as collective memory of abuse fades

status_message: On March 17, Astro Teller, in charge of the Google X R&D division, criticized the marketing of the Glass Explorer program, saying that Google did not do enough to emphasize that Glass was not a finished product. With Explorer, Google was merely trying to understand how a product like Glass would be used in the real world, Teller said.
link_name: Google exec says Google should have emphasized that Glass was not a finished product

status_message: Osborne said in his annual budget speech March 18, that the UK Office for Budget Responsibility had revised the country's growth projections from 2.4% to 2.5 in 2015, and from 2.2% to 2.3% in 2016.
link_name: UK chancellor presents positive outlook for country's economy

status_message: Ahmed Al-Rouissi, was killed in conflict in Libya, the Tunisian interior ministry said. Al-Rouissi, 48, was wanted in connection for a string of attacks including the assassination of two Tunisian politicians. He was a leader of Ansar Al-Sharia in Tunisia before joining IS in Libya.
link_name: One of Tunisia's most wanted men killed in Libya

status_message: Amazon, Best Buy, and Target began selling the Microsoft Band fitness device on March 17. They are the first non-Microsoft retailers to sell the Band, which helps tracks heart rate, steps, and calories burned. The device is also now available for pre-order in the UK, its first international market.
link_name: Amazon, Best Buy now selling Microsoft Band fitness device

status_message: A report released March 16 by BP is accused of minimizing the impact of the 2010 oil spill, including selecting studies favorable to BP's assessment the region affected by the spill is "rebounding". Federal and state officials say this conclusion is "premature".
link_name: BP report minimizes environmental impact of the 2010 oil spill, regulators say

status_message: On March 17, the country's largest Presbyterian denomination, Presbyterian Church (USA), voted 87-41 in favor to change the definition of marriage in the church constitution to from "a man and a woman" to "two people, traditionally a man and a woman." The vote included 171 regional bodies, or presbyteries.
link_name: Presbyterian Church ratifies constitution to include same-sex marriage

status_message: Police sealed off areas of a former prison farm where mass graves were found. Forensics experts will examine nearly 100 remains to determine the causes of death. Officials believe the bones belong to prison laborers from the 1960's and 70's, but have not ruled out they are more recent.
link_name: Mass grave found on apartheid-era prison farm in South Africa

status_message: The European Parliament's internal market and consumer protection committee met March 16-17 to consider the deployment of cables to make eCalls more effective. The eCall system is not intended to track people, an EU spokesperson said in Dec. 2014.
link_name: EU considers installing cables to help automated vehicle calls in emergencies

status_message: Lee's health has "deteriorated further," the Prime Minister's Office announced March 18. The 91-year-old was admitted to a hospital on Feb. 5 for severe pneumonia. He remains in the ICU in critical condition.
link_name: Health of former Singapore leader Lee worsens

status_message: Indonesia said March 17 that it is ending the search and recovery operation for the remains of the 56 people still missing, and presumed dead. The remains of 106 people have been recovered. Three bodies were recovered March 14.
link_name: Search ending for AirAsia crash victims

status_message: Missouri executed Cecil Clayton, 74, late March 17 after the U.S. Supreme Court refused to stay the execution due to his brain injury. Clayton, who lost 20% of his frontal lobe in a 1972 sawmill accident, shot and killed a sheriff's deputy in 1996.
link_name: Missouri executes inmate with severe brain injury

status_message: With 99% of the votes counted by early March 18, Netanyahu's Likud party won at least 29 of the 120 seats, with the Zionist Union winning 24 seats. The Joint Arab List received 14 seats, Yesh Atid 11 seats and Moshe Kahlon 10 seats.
link_name: Netanyahu's party takes most seats in election

status_message: Windows 10 to be released "this summer" says Microsoft http://cir.ca/news/microsoft-windows-10
link_name: Windows 10 to be available in summer 2015

status_message: An envelope addressed to the White House tested positive for cyanide March 17, according to the Secret Service. The agency did not say who the envelope was addressed to.
link_name: Secret Service confirms letter sent to White House tests positive for cyanide
Study: vaccine rate of 50%-86% helped drive Disneyland measles outbreak
Report: Rand Paul to announce 2016 White House run
Americans are drinking less coffee
Food industry fighting against added-sugar label proposal
Oracle blames strengthening US dollar for revenue miss
Meerkat adds in-app search after being cut off from Twitter social graph

status_message: Rep. Michael McCaul (R-TX), who chairs the House Homeland Security Committee, said March 17 that the U.S. was responsible for Internet outages in North Korea in Dec. 2014. He said the outages were part of a "cyber response" in retaliation for the cyberattack on Sony Pictures. He is the first U.S. official to say on the record that the U.S. was behind the outage.
link_name: Sony confirms $15 million in cyberattack costs

status_message: Benjamin Netanyahu has declared victory in Israel elections, ahead of official results.
link_name: Live Updates: Israel's election
DR Congo frees US diplomat following arrest at pro-democracy rally
Facebook to add money-sending feature to Messenger
Police chief admits failures responsible for 1989 Hillsborough stadium disaster
Former lawyer of Pakistani doctor who helped find Bin Laden shot dead

status_message: Twitter said March 17 that users who file a harassment report for the company to investigate can now easily make a copy of that report to bring to police. The report contains the name of the account being harassed, the name of the harassing account, and a URL to the harassing tweet.
link_name: Twitter creating harassment reports to give to police
US Air Force vet charged with trying to join Islamic State militant group

status_message: The company said in a statement that it has held forums on race across the country with about 2,000 employees participating. Schultz said the effort is "an opportunity to begin to re-examine how we can create a more empathetic and inclusive society - one conversation at a time."
link_name: Starbucks to encourage baristas to talk about race in America
Ukrainian lawmakers approve 'special status' for rebel-held eastern Ukraine
Sony confirms $15 million in cyberattack costs
House GOP proposes budget that cuts $5.5 trillion in spending over 10 years
Yahoo debuts first two episodes of new 'Community' season

status_message: At the start of final arguments in the inquiry into Litvinenko's death on March 16, a UK court heard written testimony by Litvinenko's close friend Boris Berezovsky, who was found dead in his Surrey home in March 2013. The testimony, made in 2007, claims Litvinenko was investigating Russian mob activity in Spain.
link_name: Litvinenko was investigating Russian mob activity abroad, UK inquiry hears

status_message: FBI agents provided weapons, money and encouragement to Sami Osmakac, who was convicted in Nov. 2014 to 40 years in prison on weapons charges, a March 16 report in The Intercept found. The report, based on transcripts of an FBI sting operation, points to dozens of cases in which agents and informants have led would-be plotters.
link_name: FBI transcripts question authenticity of anti-terrorism raids

status_message: The U.S. government returned more than 60 artifacts to Iraq, the Dept. of Homeland Security said March 16. The items smuggled into the U.S. after the 2003 U.S.-led invasion of Iraq include the head of a limestone statue of Assyrian King Sargon II. More than 1,200 items have been repatriated since 2008.
link_name: US returns looted artifacts to Iraq

status_message: Multiple publications, including Bloomberg and 9 to 5 Mac, reported March 16 that Apple is planning to expand its trade-in program to include Android and BlackBerry devices. According to the reports, customers would be able to trade in these devices for credit toward a new iPhone. The program is expected to launch within the next few weeks.
link_name: Reports: Apple to let customers trade Android phones for iPhones

status_message: Voting opened at 10,372 polling stations for Israel's parliament, the Knesset. There are 5,881,696 eligible voters. Turnout by mid-morning was 13.7%, which was higher than turnout at the same time in the previous two elections, the Elections Authority said.
link_name: Israelis vote in test of Netanyahu's leadership

status_message: A slab of concrete fell on Elis Kurniasih, 33, a domestic worker from Indonesia, as she was sleeping on a balcony of her employment agency. Kurniasih died from her injuries March 16, the South China Morning Post reported. Kurniasih left behind two children.
link_name: Hong Kong domestic worker killed while sleeping on balcony of employment agency

status_message: Pakistan executed 12 men on March 17, the largest number of people executed on the same day since Dec. 2014. A total of 27 people have been hanged since the capital punishment ban ended. Reuters reported on March 17 that the policy has widened to everyone on death row, or more than 8,000 people.
link_name: Pakistan executes a dozen people in one day

status_message: Romney and Holyfield will spar in a charity event in Salt Lake City on May 15 for Charity Vision, which supplies medical eye equipment to doctors in disadvantaged parts of the world. "It will either be a very short fight, or I will be knocked unconscious," Romney said.
link_name: Mitt Romney to participate in charity fight with Evander Holyfield

status_message: The WSJ, citing "people familiar with the matter" said March 16 that Apple is in talks with TV networks to create a TV streaming service that will play on all iOS devices, including Apple TV. The service, according to the report, would have "about 25 channels" and would cost "about $30 to $40 a month."
link_name: Report: Apple in talks with networks to launch online streaming TV service

status_message: Closing arguments began on March 16 and are expected to last several days. The 12 defendants could face decades behind bars if convicted. Of the 35 initially indicted in the case, 21 reached plea agreements and two died during the course of the trial, which opened in Sept. 2014.
link_name: Closing arguments begin in Atlanta teachers cheating scandal case
Baseball commissioner will consider Pete Rose's latest request for reinstatement
Police describe shootout with Tsarnaev brothers, Tamerlan's death
Pinterest reaches $11 billion valuation with latest funding round
UK Parliament: GCHQ should be subjected to stricter regulation
Rory McIlroy will replace Tiger Woods as face of golf video game
Egypt court sentences Muslim Brotherhood leader, 13 others, to death

status_message: Adidas announced on March 16 that it will no longer pursue a new contract with the NBA when its current deal expires at the end of the 2016-17 season. Adidas and the NBA originally partnered in 2006, when they agreed to 11-year deal worth $400 million.
link_name: Adidas will not pursue renewal deal with NBA

status_message: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said during an interview March 16 that if he is reelected, there will be no Palestinian state. The statement is a change from his position in 2009 when he said he supported a two-state solution.
link_name: Netanyahu says if he is reelected, there will be no Palestinian state
Congressional approval rating at 18%
Bill to allow direct Tesla sales passes NJ Senate
Putin orders show of Russian military force
CDC: Baby boomers more likely to accidentally overdose than those aged 25-44
Japanese firm Nomura claims it 'did nothing wrong' in selling bad mortgages
HP wins preliminary approval of Autonomy settlement with shareholders
Flight crew identified in deadly Black Hawk crash that killed 11
ACLU suing Obama administration for 'kill list' involving drone strikes
HHS Secretary says 16.4 million people have gained insurance due to Obamacare
Robert Durst won't fight extradition, will face murder charges in California

status_message: Facebook released its latest transparency report on March 16. Government requests for user data worldwide increased from 34,946 in the first half of 2014 to 35,051 in the second half of 2014.
link_name: Facebook: Government requests for account data continues to rise

status_message: Venezuela's National Assembly voted March 15 to give Maduro powers to govern by decree through Dec. 31. Maduro said he needs the powers, which he previously received, to deal with diplomatic confrontations with the U.S. The opposition, however, says the powers can subvert civil rights.
link_name: Venezuela's president given decree powers again

status_message: Two men were shot and killed in their car another vehicle pulled up beside them and the people inside fired multiple gunshots, Chicago police said. In addition to the double homicide, at least 14 other people were shot and injured in Chicago on March 13-15.
link_name: Two killed in continuing gun violence in Chicago

status_message: Shortly after the March 15 bombings, rioters beat to death two suspected associates of the bombers. Up to 4,000 people took to the streets in Lahore. Protests occurred other cities including Karachi, Peshawar, Multan and Quetta.
link_name: Deadly attacks on two churches in Pakistan spark riots, protests

status_message: Blackstone's head of real estate Jonathan Gray told the Wall Street Journal March 15 that the company has entered into a deal to purchase the iconic tower, Chicago's tallest building. Blackstone Group is a private equity firm.
link_name: Blackstone to buy Willis Tower in Chicago for $1.3 billion

status_message: Kentucky enters the NCAA tournament at 34-0 after defeating Arkansas 78-63 in the SEC championship. Indiana completed the last perfect season in men's NCAA basketball in 1976. Kentucky is the fourth team since then to enter the tournament with a perfect record.
link_name: Undefeated Kentucky given overall top seed in NCAA tournament

status_message: "Cinderella" opened with $70.1 million at the North American box office March 13-15. The movie, directed by Kenneth Branagh, also earned $62.4 million overseas, including $25 million in China, a March opening record for the country.
link_name: "Cinderella" earns $70.1 million in opening weekend

status_message: Vladimir Putin was seen meeting with Italian Prime Minister Matteo Renzi at the Kremlin on March 5. Since then he has not made any public appearances, fueling speculation about his health and whereabouts.
link_name: Speculation over Vladimir Putin's whereabouts after days without appearance

status_message: On March 15, almost 1 million Brazilians marched in peaceful protests in more than 50 cities calling for the ouster of President Dilma Rousseff. Protesters insist Rousseff, the former board chair of Brazil's state-owned oil company Petrobras, had to be aware of alleged corruption and political bribes that took place at Petrobras under her watch.
link_name: Brazilian protesters call for impeachment of President Rousseff

status_message: St. Louis County police announced March 15 that an arrest had been made in connection to the shooting of two police officers outside of the Ferguson Police Department.
link_name: Police arrest suspect in shooting of 2 officers in Ferguson

status_message: The families of nine Sandy Hook victims have filed a lawsuit against the estate of Nancy Lanza for failing to properly secure the AR-15 rifle that her son used to kill 26 people in Dec. 2012.
link_name: Sandy Hook families sue estate of killer's mother

status_message: Robert Durst was arrested March 14 in New Orleans. Durst, 71, is the subject of a HBO documentary series, "The Jinx," centered around Durst's suspected involvement in two murders and his wife's 1982 disappearance.
link_name: Robert Durst, subject of HBO documentary, arrested on murder charges

status_message: With the use of the Hubble Space Telescope, NASA has discovered that the largest moon in our solar system, Jupiter's moon Ganymede, has a deep salt water ocean that is approximately 60 miles deeper than Earth's oceans and is buried 95 miles below the planet's icy crust.
link_name: NASA discovers massive ocean on Jupiter's moon, Ganymede

status_message: Two audits released by the Office of Inspector General in March revealed Social Security Administration (SSA) records that say 6.5 million people in the U.S. have reached the age of 112 (between 35-42 people that age are known worldwide), and at least $17.1 million in benefits have been paid to dead people.
link_name: New Social Security reports show millions of inaccurate records, fraud

status_message: An unspecified number of American aid workers were among at least 10 people who were potentially exposed to Ebola in Sierra Leone and evacuated from the country on March 14.
link_name: Several US aid workers evacuated from Sierra Leone after possible Ebola exposure

status_message: Kurdish authorities said March 14 they have evidence that IS forces used chlorine gas as a chemical weapon against their peshmerga troops in northern Iraq during an attack in January.
link_name: Kurdish forces allege Islamic State chlorine gas attack in Iraq

status_message: The New York Times reported March 14 that so-called "ghost money" has inadvertently ended up in the hands of Al-Qaeda. The report is based on letters used as evidence against an accused Pakistani Al-Qaeda operative in Brooklyn, detailing a $5 million ransom payment in 2010 to free an Afghan diplomat.
link_name: Report: CIA 'ghost money' in Afghanistan inadvertently bankrolled Al-Qaeda
CDC reports three Listeria deaths linked to Blue Bell ice cream

status_message: Japan's Nikkei 225 Stock Average closed at 19,254 on March 13, its highest close since April 2000.
link_name: Japan's Nikkei 225 closes above 19,000 for first time since 2000

status_message: Twitter confirmed March 13 that it is no longer allowing Meerkat to tap its social graph, meaning that new users who sign up no longer automatically follow their Twitter followers.
link_name: Meerkat cut off from Twitter's social graph
German court orders skeptic to pay $106,300 after losing bet on measles existence
Portland Uber driver sues company over data breach

status_message: Cyclone Pam hit the island nation of Vanuatu with 168mph winds, tearing off roofs and knocking out electricity in the capital of Port Vila.
link_name: Cyclone devastates Vanuatu islands

status_message: Following eight crash tests by the Federal Highway Administration (FHWA), regulators said March 13 Trinity's guardrail system met all safety requirements. The guardrails, which were accused of spearing vehicles instead of slowing them, didn't penetrate any of the test cars.
link_name: Guardrails blamed for deaths pass federal crash test criteria

status_message: The New York Mets said in a statement March 13 that the team has settled the lawsuit with a fired former senior vice president. The terms of the settlement were not disclosed.
link_name: Former NY Mets exec settles discrimination lawsuit over unwed pregnancy
'Slender Man' teens accused of stabbing girl to stand trial as adults

status_message: An adult league player, 36-year-old Bassel Saad, was sentenced on March 13 to between 8 and 15 years in prison after his punch killed a referee in June 2014.
link_name: Detroit-area soccer player gets 8-15 years in prison for punching, killing referee

status_message: Police arrested former Maldives president Mohamed Nasheed Feb. 22, under anti-terrorism laws. The arrest was related to an order he made as president in 2012 to arrest a judge, according to prosecution documents. Nasheed, a former journalist and member of parliament, has been imprisoned several times.
link_name: Maldives former president sentenced to 13 years for ordering judge's arrest

status_message: Without committing a crime, Oregon man jailed for 900 days
link_name: Without committing a crime, Oregon man jailed for 900 days

status_message: On March 12, one week after President Obama called the proposed law "bad...for the global economy as a whole," Chinese authorities unexpectedly put a proposed counterterrorism law on hold.
link_name: China puts proposed counterterrorism law on hold

status_message: The U.S. State Department said March 13 it is working with lawmakers to provide $70 million in new non-lethal aid for Syrian rebels. If approved, the money would bring the total aid offered by the U.S. to Syrian rebels to nearly $400 million.
link_name: State Dept. seeks $70 million in new non-lethal aid for Syrian rebels

status_message: State telecommunications company Etecsa approved Cuba's first free, public internet service at a Havana cultural center run by famed artist Kcho. The unprecedented move marks the loosening of strict regulations regarding Internet use on the island.
link_name: Cuba okays first free public Wi-Fi at cultural center

status_message: Germany's Commerzbank pays $1.5 billion settlement for sanctions violations http://cir.ca/news/doj-pursues-european-banks-for-sanctions-violations
link_name: Germany's Commerzbank pays $1.5 billion settlement for sanctions violations

status_message: Google leaks personal information of 283,000 registered domains
link_name: Google leaks personal information of 283,000 registered domains

status_message: The powdered alcohol sold by the company Palcohol had previously been approved by the bureau in 2014, but it was rescinded after the bureau said approval of Palcohol's labels were given in error. The company says it plans to begin selling its product by summer of 2015.
link_name: Federal regulators approve powdered alcohol for sale in the US

status_message: On March 13, Bloomberg reported that the FBI is investigating contractors hired by hedge fund manager William Ackman for potentially making false statements to regulators about Ackman's hedge fund's manipulation of Herbalife stock in 2012. Ackman said neither he nor his firm had been served with a subpoena.
link_name: FBI probes Ackman contractors for wrongdoing in Herbalife manipulation

status_message: The Nintendo 3DS was the top selling video game hardware platform in the U.S. in February, Nintendo said March 12, citing data from the NPD research firm. A total of 395,000 3DS consoles were sold in the month, the "great majority" of which were the New 3DS XL, which was released on Feb. 13.
link_name: Nintendo 3DS tops US video game sales in February
Apple launches public beta program for iOS
Book: Steve Jobs rejected Tim Cook's liver transplant offer

status_message: Ukraine received the first $5 billion of a $17.5 billion loan under a recent deal with the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the finance ministry confirmed March 13. Around $2.2 billion will go to reserve purchases by the central bank, while $2.8 billion are allocated to the federal budget, it said.
link_name: Ukraine receives first $5 billion of IMF loan
CDC recommends new vaccine effective against 9 strains of HPV
US oil workers close to reaching deal on wages, safety standards
Iranian nuclear deal could include measures at the UN
American healthcare worker with Ebola arrives in Maryland for treatment
Report: Microsoft to release Android, iOS versions of Cortana
Turkey arrests suspected coalition spy for helping British girls join Islamic State

status_message: International Relief and Development (IRD) held leadership retreats at the exclusive Nemacolin Woodlands Resort in Pennsylvania and parties at the Air and Space Museum from 2007-2010, the Washington Post reported March 13. IRD billed the U.S. government $1.1 million.
link_name: USAID awarded $2.4B to contractor that splurged on luxury retreats and parties

status_message: Swedish prosecutors offered on March 13 to question Assange in London rather than waiting for the completion of extradition proceedings that started in 2010, the Swedish Prosecution Authority said. Assange's lawyer called it a "big victory," but said permissions from the UK and Ecuador could take time.
link_name: Swedish prosecutor offers to question Julian Assange in London

status_message: The UK announced March 12 that it planned to be a founding member of the Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank (AIIB). The White House subsequently released a statement urging the UK to push the bank to have high standards, something it has previously voiced concern over.
link_name: US criticizes UK decision to join Asian bank to rival World Bank, IMF

status_message: 23andMe CEO Anne Wojcicki said March 12 the company will launch a drug research and development unit. 23andMe will look for potential drug targets for rare and common diseases based on the genetic information found in its database of 850,000 customers.
link_name: Genetic testing startup 23andMe to begin drug research and development

status_message: On March 12, NASA launched an Atlas V rocket carrying four satellites, which will conduct two years of research on the collision between the Earth's and the Sun's magnetic fields. The Magnetospheric Multiscale Mission (MMS) satellites will deploy about 90 minutes after the launch.
link_name: NASA launches satellites to study collisions between Sun's and Earth's magnetic fields
Michael Graves, pioneer of architectural Postmodernism, dead at 80

status_message: The Swiss euthanasia organization, Exit, which helps arrange physician-assisted suicides, announced on March 11 that it has seen record growth with a total membership of over 86,000 people.
link_name: Switzerland right-to-die organization sees record increase in membership

status_message: The National Institutes of Health (NIH) said March 12 that an American healthcare worker in Sierra Leone has tested positive for Ebola and will be flown to Maryland for treatment at the NIH Clinical Center Special Clinical Studies Unit. NIH did not release details about the worker.
link_name: American healthcare worker with Ebola to be flown to US for treatment

status_message: The Dow gained 260 points, March 12, to close at 17,895. The index recovered only some of its losses from March 10 when it dived 333 points. Speculation on when the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates continues to play havoc with the markets.
link_name: Dow picks up 260 pts, back in positive territory for 2015

status_message: WHO reported March 12 that the Ebola death toll had reached 10,004 people, mostly in the three West African Countries most affected by the outbreak. A total of 24,350 cases have been reported since the outbreak began.
link_name: As Ebola outbreak wanes, death toll tops 10,000

status_message: The "Frozen" sequel was announced following a meeting of Disney shareholders on March 12. The company said co-directors Chris Buck and Jennifer Lee will return to make the second film. Details, including the release date, have not yet been announced.
link_name: Disney to make 'Frozen' sequel

status_message: Rev. Willie Barrow, a co-founder of the movement that became People United to Serve Humanity (Operation PUSH) alongside Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., and Rev. Jesse Jackson, passed away at her home in Chicago on March 12.
link_name: Willie Barrow, civil rights activist, dies at 90
Ranchers in South Africa breed mutant animals to hunt

status_message: Ridesharing service Lyft confirmed March 11 that it raised $530 million in a funding round led by Rakuten, a Japanese e-commerce company. The round brings Lyft's total funding to more than $860 million.
link_name: Lyft raises $530 million to fund further expansion

status_message: Pratchett had authored more than 70 books, most of which take place in the "Discworld" -- a universe in which the world is flat, and is balance on the back of four elephants, which are themselves on the back of giant turtle. His books which were noted for their sharp satire and humor sold more than 75 million copies. He was the most read British author of the 1990s before being overtaken by JK Rowling.
link_name: Fantasy author Terry Pratchett dies at 66

status_message: Dadayev, the prime suspect in the Nemtsov murder trial, on March 10 told a prisoners' rights monitoring group the confession that led to his conviction was coerced. Dadayev told Yeva Merkachyova of the Public Oversight Commission (POC) he was shackled for two days with a bag over his head before signing a confession.
link_name: Suspect in Boris Nemtsov shooting says confession was coerced

status_message: Timothy Camus, deputy inspector general for the IRS, said March 12 that the agency has received 366,000 reports of scam calls since 2013. So far, 3,052 taxpayers have had $15.5 million stolen. One individual was scammed out of over $500,000.
link_name: IRS says more than 366,000 taxpayers have been targets of phone scam

status_message: The interior and justice ministers of the 28 member states of the EU will meet March 12 to discuss setting up a counter-terrorism unit to combat extremist content online. According to the FT, EU officials will present a plan, which includes tech companies, in Brussels that day.
link_name: EU seeks tech companies' cooperation in removing extremist content online

status_message: New Hampshire state representatives passed a bill 297-67 that would decriminalize the possession of small amounts of marijuana (14 grams) on March 11. The new bill calls for possession to be treated like traffic violations. This is the sixth time the NH House has passed a marijuana decriminalization law; previous bills never made it past the Senate.
link_name: New Hampshire House votes to decriminalize small amounts of marijuana

status_message: Intel on March 12 lowered its Q1 2015 revenue forecast from $13.7 billion to $12.8 billion. The company blamed "weaker than expected demand for business desktop PCs" for the downward estimate.
link_name: Intel slashes Q1 2015 revenue forecast by nearly $1 billion
Dutch court strikes down data retention law

status_message: The overall net worth of U.S. households grew 1.9% from October to December, reaching $83 trillion -- a new record, the Federal Reserve said March 12.
link_name: Household net worth reaches record $83 trillion in final quarter of 2014
Netherlands hit with more cases of H5N8 bird flu
Utah passes LGBT rights bill, with Mormon support
FCC publishes net neutrality rules online
Chinese lawmakers want to exert influence on Dalai Lama's succession
Juries to determine employment status of Uber, Lyft drivers
4 killed in cement factory collapse in Bangladesh
New Mexico lawmaker moves to exempt lead bullets from EPA oversight
Appeals court upholds dismissal of manslaughter charges in 2010 oil spill
Doctors' group: Syrian government has killed nearly 600 medical personnel
Foles, Bradford, Graham among blockbuster moves in NFL
UN torture investigator accuses US of preventing prison visits

status_message: The ESA planned to begin checking for communications coming from the Philae lander on March 12. The ESA still does not know the exact location of the probe, or how much power it has.
link_name: European Space Agency checking for possible comet probe communications

status_message: Jahanzeb Malik, 33, appeared at a hearing via videolink from an Ontario jail. He has been in custody since March 9. The Canada Border Services Agency (CBSA) accuses him of attempting to recruit an undercover officer to help him bomb the U.S. Consulate in Toronto. His next hearing is March 16.
link_name: Canada aims to deport man suspected of plot on U.S. consulate

status_message: Manuel Vasquez, 46, was executed by lethal injection and pronounced dead at 6:32pm on March 11 in Huntsville, TX. Vasquez was sentenced to death for the 1998 strangulation of Juanita Ybarra, 51. His execution leaves the state with one dose of the drugs it uses for executions.
link_name: Texas has one lethal dose remaining after latest execution

status_message: Shots were fired outside of the Ferguson police station around midnight on March 12, according to witnesses. Ferguson police Lt. Col Al Eickhoff said two police officers were hit, according to the St. Louis Post-Dispatch. Images on social media showed police with weapons drawn in search of the shooter/s.
link_name: Two police officers shot during anti-police protest in Ferguson

status_message: Three lawmakers surrendered in Pennsylvania's capital city March 10 and were arraigned on conspiracy and bribery charges. Prosecutors say Rep. Michelle Brownlee, and former Rep. Harold James have admitted to taking bribes; Rep. Louise Williams Bishop has not admitted guilt.
link_name: Three more Penn. state lawmakers arrested in corruption sting

status_message: The Guardian on March 11 issued several clarifications regarding its late 2014 article about alleged Whisper privacy violations. Among other clarifications, the publication walked back claims regarding Whisper tracking the location of its users via their I.P. address.
link_name: The Guardian issues correction on article about Whisper privacy violations

status_message: Enterprise cloud storage and services company Box on March 11 released its Q4 2014 financial results. The company posted a loss of $1.65 per share on $63 million in revenue. Analysts were expecting a loss of $1.17 per share and $57.99 million in revenue. This was the first time Box reported its financial results as a public company.
link_name: Box falls 8% following mixed Q4 2014 results

status_message: The British government announced on March 11 that a military healthcare worker in Sierra Leone tested positive for the Ebola virus. Between 600 and 700 UK personnel are currently stationed in Sierra Leone to assist in the fight against the deadly virus.
link_name: UK military healthcare worker in Sierra Leone tests positive for Ebola

status_message: A Cuban state telecommunications company said Mar. 11 that Cuba and the U.S. have established a direct telephone link, the first since 1997. In the past, the two countries were forced to connect at a higher cost through a third country. The connection was set up through U.S. company Domestic Telecom.
link_name: Second round of US-Cuba negotiations held in Washington

status_message: Shake Shack reported March 11 a net loss of $1.4 million, or 5 cents per share, in the first quarter since its IPO. Revenue rose to $35 million from $23 million year earlier but the company was also hit with an after-tax charge of $1.1 million related to the IPO. Same-restaurant sales rose 7.2%, beating analysts expectations of 4%.
link_name: Shake Shack reports net loss in first earnings report

status_message: The move, first reported by Reuters, may happen in the second half of 2015. A $1 billion IPO could value the broadcaster at $29 billion, including debt. Univision has declined to comment on the move.
link_name: Univision seeks $1 billion IPO

status_message: DiNapoli said Mar. 11 that the average Wall Street bonus rose to $172,860 in 2014, the highest amount since 2007. The bonus pool increased $28.5 billion, up 3%. The report presented by DiNapoli said the nation's largest banks profited 8.5% less than the year before.
link_name: Average Wall Street bonus was $172,860 in 2014, highest since 2007

status_message: Multiple reports, from Fox News, CBS and others say Ferguson Police Chief Thomas Jackson will resign on March 11. The city of Ferguson and the police department have not commented on the claims. CNN reported that Jackson is willing to step down, but hopes to ensure that the department will still exist.
link_name: Ferguson police chief will step down

status_message: The executive board of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) has approved a $17.5B loan to the Ukrainian government over four years, it said March 11. Ukraine must enact the IMF's structural adjustment reforms. The country already has $7.3B external debt payments due in 2015.
link_name: IMF approves $17.5 billion loan to Ukraine

status_message: In a March 11 vote, UK lawmakers voted to introduce standardized packaging for cigarettes. If the law passes a vote in the House of Lords, tobacco companies will be forced to sell cigarettes in plain brown packets with minimal branding. The UK smoking rate fell below 20%, an 80-year low, in 2014.
link_name: UK lawmakers vote to ban branding on cigarette packages

status_message: More than 40% of U.S. homes subscribed to at least one streaming video service as of Nov. 2014, according to a Nielsen report published on March 11. Netflix was the most popular service with 36% penetration, followed by Amazon Instant Video (13%) and Hulu Plus (6.5%).
link_name: Nielsen: 40% of US homes subscribe to a streaming video service

status_message: NASCAR reinstated Kurt Busch on March 11. Busch was suspended on Feb. 20 after he was accused of abusing his former girlfriend, Patricia Driscoll, during an argument in Sept. 2014. Due to the suspension, Busch missed three races but will remain eligible for the Chase for the NASCAR Sprint Cup after NASCAR granted him a waiver.
link_name: NASCAR reinstates Kurt Busch after domestic violence suspension
Apple blames internal DNS error for App Store downtime
Texas may run out of drug used in lethal injections by March 18
IS assault on Kurds seeks to reclaim territory in northeast Syria
Apple asks for dismissal of electric car battery maker's lawsuit
Colombian government to stop FARC air raids as part of peace process
Aereo sues broadcasters over lackluster asset auction
Barcelona brothel workers gain employment rights
11 missing after military helicopter crashes in Florida

status_message: Pao gave testimony March 10-11 on KPCB workplace practices. She accused the company of excluding female junior partners from important meetings and failing to act on her sexual harassment complaints against a colleague. KPCB has worked with major companies like Amazon, Netscape and Google.
link_name: Court hears claims of sexism from former venture capital employee
Parents of former Thai princess jailed for defamation

status_message: Broad Sustainable Building chairman Zhang Yue said in early March that his company had built a prefabricated skyscraper at a rate of three stories per day. The building has 800 apartments, which are for employees of the company, as well as office space and atriums.
link_name: Chinese company builds 57-story modular apartment building in 19 days

status_message: The Iraqi military and militias took over large parts of Tikrit, the home city of Saddam Hussein, in the first major offensive against IS in Iraq. Most of the IS militants in the city retreated, security officials said. The four-pronged assault continued into March 11.
link_name: Iraqi troops and militia taking over Tikrit in offensive against Islamic State

status_message: Sens. Cory Booker (D-N.J.), Kirsten Gillibrand (D-N.Y.) and Rand Paul (R-Ky.) introduced legislation on March 10 to end the federal prohibition on medical marijuana. The law would reclassify marijuana for the Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA), open research, give access to military veterans and allow banking services.
link_name: Three US Senators introduce medical marijuana bill

status_message: The Chinese government has approved a plan for two reactors to be built at an existing plant in Liaoning Province, the China General Nuclear Power Corporation said March 10. No date for the construction or completion of the reactors was given. Other government approvals are also needed.
link_name: China approves construction of nuclear reactors

status_message: An emergency session of parliament sat on March 10 to push through amendments controlling the use of crystal meth, ecstasy and other psychoactive drugs. Technically, the possession and use of these was legal until the amendments are passed March 11.
link_name: Possession of ecstasy, other drugs legal in Ireland for a day

status_message: Berta Soler won 108 of 233 votes in the first referendum on her leadership. She needs five more votes to win. Soler announced a second vote is set for March 16.
link_name: Prominent Cuban human rights group to rerun vote on leader

status_message: Jurors were shown photographs March 10 of the message Tsarnaev wrote inside a boat before his capture. The prosecution argued Tsarnaev's writings, as well as his two Twitter accounts, show he was a self-radicalized terrorist. Tsarnaev's attorney countered that some of the tweets, including the tweet "I shall die young," were pop culture references and rap lyrics.
link_name: Boston bombing trial jurors see Tsarnaev's handwritten defense of attack

status_message: Japan will hold a moment of silence at 2:46pm on Mar. 11 to commemorate when the 9.0 earthquake struck off the northeast coast four years earlier.
link_name: Japan marks fourth anniversary of tsunami; 80,000 still in temporary housing

status_message: The Utah Senate voted to reintroduce firing squads late on March 10. Utah Gov. Gary Herbert has not said whether he will sign the bill. Herbert spokesperson Marty Carpenter said in a statement March 10 that the state will look for ways to get lethal injection drugs in the future.
link_name: Utah legislature passes bill to reintroduce firing squads for capital punishment

status_message: Philadelphia reverses 110 convictions linked to officers accused of corruption
link_name: Philadelphia reverses 110 convictions linked to officers accused of corruption

status_message: AT&T debuts original series for Snapchat
link_name: AT&T debuts original series for Snapchat

status_message: Jury awards $7.3 million to Marvin Gaye family in 'Blurred Lines' lawsuit http://cir.ca/news/blurred-lines-lawsuit
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Report: CIA helped Justice Dept. develop aerial phone-scanning tech http://cir.ca/news/us-marshals-planes-as-cell-towers-1
link_name: Report: CIA helped Justice Dept. develop aerial phone-scanning tech

status_message: Google CFO Patrick Pichette to retire http://cir.ca/news/google-financial-results
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Target said on March 3 that it would implement a plan to cut $2 billion in costs through restructuring, including layoffs at its corporate headquarters over two years. The move is part of a plan to streamline operations and customize merchandizing decisions based on location.
link_name: Target to lay off 1,700 workers

status_message: The dollar reached a 12-year high against the euro and yen, March 10, on the back of speculation that the Federal Reserve could raise interest rates starting in the summer and continued uncertainty around Greece and the eurozone. Investors believe recent strong jobs data and signals from the Fed could mean a rate increase as soon as July.
link_name: Fed interest rate speculation pushes dollar to 12-year highs against euro, yen

status_message: Archaeologists from the Egyptian Ministry of Antiquities and the American Research Center (ARC) found a tomb that is at least 3,300 years old, the ministry said on March 10. The tomb, which includes various scenes painted on plaster, was robbed in antiquity. It is adjacent to a tomb found a week earlier.
link_name: Egyptologists find second ancient tomb in Luxor in a week

status_message: Sony will release the PS4 in China on March 20 for around $463, the company confirmed March 10. The console was originally scheduled to be released on Jan. 11 but was delayed following a request from the Chinese government to make an unspecified "adjustment to the business plan."
link_name: Sony to release PS4 in China on March 20

status_message: About 95 people escaped from a prison run by the Islamic State (IS) northeast of Aleppo, a UK-based monitoring group said. The group included Kurdish fighters, fighters from battalions opposed to IS, and civilians. Witnesses in the town heard loudspeakers ordering residents to help recapture escapees.
link_name: Nearly 100 people escape Islamic State prison in Syria
Fraternity kicked off Univ. of Oklahoma campus after video of racist chant

status_message: U.S. transit riders took 10.75 billion trips in 2014, up 0.95% from 2013, according to a March 3 report by the American Public Transportation Association (APTA). For 9 years in a row, U.S. transit ridership has topped 10 billion.
link_name: US public transit ridership reaches 58-year high in 2014
Apple donates $50 million to minority organizations to improve diversity

status_message:
Director pleads guilty in the first-ever conviction for a death on a movie set. 

Filmmaker Randall Miller pleaded guilty to involuntary manslaughter and criminal trespassing charges after a camera assistant, Sarah Jones, was killed Feb. 20, 2014, on the set of his film 'Midnight Rider.'
link_name: Director pleads guilty in on-set death of camera assistant
Protests run into third day after police shooting in Wisconsin capital
Former Ivory Coast first lady and military leaders sentenced to 20 years
Former judicial chief selected to head Iran's top clerical body
ICC wants UN help to arrest Sudanese President Bashir
Wikipedia suing NSA over mass surveillance

status_message: Incepta Pharmaceuticals started selling a 12-week course of the drug, under the generic brand name Hopetavir, for $900, or $10 a pill, on March 8. Patent-holder Gilead Sciences Inc. sells a course of the drug for $84,000 in the U.S.
link_name: Bangladeshi company sells generic version of $1,000 Hepatitis C pill for $10
Report: CIA has spent years trying to crack Apple's hardware encryption

status_message: Police used batons to beat back around 200 students who tried to break through police-erected barriers outside the Letpadan monastery about 90 miles north of Yangon on March 10. The extent of injuries was unclear from initial reports. Pictures appeared to show police detaining protesters.
link_name: Burmese police beat back student protesters

status_message: Slumdog Millionaire star, Freida Pinto, and Meryl Streep held a candlelight vigil with about 650 people on March 10 for the Delhi gang rape victim, Jyoti Singh. The vigil occurred at the U.S. premiere of the controversial BBC documentary "India's Daughter."
link_name: India's attempt to ban rape documentary draws attention to it

status_message: Pakistan successfully tested the Shaheen-III surface-to-surface ballistic missile on March 9. It can carry nuclear and conventional warheads. It launched from Rawalpindi into the Arabian Sea, according to a statement by the Pakistani military. The missile has a range of about 1,709 miles, which is longer than its predecessors.
link_name: Pakistan tests long-range, nuclear-capable missile

status_message: A pair of helicopters collided on March 9, killing all 10 people among the two craft. The helicopters were taking part in the filming of a popular French celebrity reality TV show called "Dropped."
link_name: Deadly helicopter collision occurs in filming of French reality show in Argentina

status_message: A 47-year-old woman named Norchuk self-immolated in the Tibetan village of Tsotsuk in Sichuan, China, an exiled advocacy group said March 9. She is the first Tibetan believed to have died in this manner in 2015.
link_name: Tibetan woman dies from self-immolation

status_message: Ambassador Lippert was released from a Seoul hospital on March 10. South Korean President Park Geun-hye visited Lippert in the hospital a day earlier. Park was suffered a similar attack before she was president in 2010 by an attacker who used a box cutter. She received treatment at the same hospital.
link_name: US ambassador released from South Korean hospital following attack

status_message: AEG told the LA Times March 9 it had dropped its plans to build an NFL stadium in downtown Los Angeles. The company spent five years and at least $50 million on the Farmers Field project but failed to generate interest from any teams.
link_name: AEG drops plans for NFL stadium in downtown Los Angeles

status_message: The Missouri Supreme Court on March 9 appointed Judge Roy Richter of the Missouri Court of Appeals to take over cases for Ferguson's municipal court "until further order." The state's top court said the "extraordinary action" was needed "to help restore public trust and confidence in the Ferguson municipal court division."
link_name: Missouri Supreme Court takes over Ferguson municipal court after DOJ report

status_message: Kentucky State GOP leaders voted March 7 to back Rand Paul's plan to hold a presidential caucus for 2016, which would clear the way for him to run a dual race for president and Senate without breaking state laws. The plan still needs to be approved by the state's GOP central committee in August.
link_name: Kentucky GOP leaders clear way for possible Paul dual run in 2016
Supreme Court rejects lawsuits over Guantanamo Bay detainee treatment

status_message: The CBO reported March 9 that the cost of the Affordable Care Act (ACA) will be $142 billion less over 10 years than previously forecast, down to $1.207 trillion. By March 9, 11.7 million people had enrolled.
link_name: CBO cuts cost of Obamacare $142 billion over 10 years

status_message:
We are seeking a US West Coast based evening staff writer to join our editorial team at Circa.

Details here:
link_name: Circa News - US West Coast Evening Staff Writer

status_message: Jessica Kensky, a nursing student who was watching the marathon, testified March 9 for the government's case. Kensky was injured in the blast and had one leg amputated soon after; her other leg was amputated in January 2015. She said she still has 30-40 ball bearings embedded in her legs.
link_name: Survivor testimony, Tsarnaev twitter accounts in focus on day 3 of Boston bombing trial

status_message: Twitter confirmed March 9 that it recently acquired Periscope, a startup that hasn't yet launched that's developing an app to let people stream live video from their smartphone. While Twitter did not disclose how much it paid for the startup, TechCrunch reported that the deal may be worth around $100 million.
link_name: Twitter acquires Periscope video startup

status_message: Hillary Clinton will answer reporters' questions regarding the email controversy during a press conference in New York, according to a report by Politico. While a date has not been set, the report says the press conference will happen 'in the next several days.'
link_name: Hillary Clinton to answer questions regarding email controversy

status_message: Sam Simon, 59, died in his Los Angeles' home March 9. In addition to serving as a writer and executive producer for "The Simpsons," Simon is also known for his philanthropy, running the Sam Simon Foundation and contributing to numerous charities. Simon was diagnosed with terminal colon cancer in 2012.
link_name: 'The Simpsons' co-creator Sam Simon dies at 59
Federal employees can join lawsuit for being made to work during 2013 government shutdown

status_message: A United Nations report presented at the Commission on the Status of Women assembly March 9 by Secretary General Ban Ki-moon says that 35% of women around the world have experienced physical or sexual violence, if not both, in their lifetime.
link_name: UN: More than 1 in 3 women worldwide have experienced violence in their lifetime

status_message: According to a leaked document published March 8 by The Sunday Times, Tony Blair approached the United Arab Emirates with an offer to provide his services as a consultant in exchange for 30 million British pounds ($45 million).
link_name: Leaked document details Blair's plans for $45m partnership with UAE

status_message: The list of proposed reforms by the Greek government is "far from complete", the head of the eurozone finance ministers said in Brussels on March 9.
link_name: Eurozone finance ministers reject Greek list of proposed reforms

status_message: HBO announced March 9 that HBO Now will debut in early April for $14.99 per month. HBO is working with Apple as an exclusive partner in what the company called a "transformative moment." HBO made the announcement at an Apple event in San Francisco.
link_name: HBO Now standalone online service to launch on Apple TV

status_message: The Obama administration said March 9 that it has imposed economic sanctions on seven Venezuelan officials over alleged human rights abuses.
link_name: US imposes sanctions against 7 Venezuelan officials for human rights violations

status_message: "Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt" was picked up by Netflix in Nov. 2014 and debuted on March 6. The comedy, which was originally picked up NBC and stars Ellie Kemper as the main character, was widely praised by critics, with the AV Club saying it "exemplifies what a Netflix sitcom should be."
link_name: Tina Fey's 'Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt' makes Netflix debut

status_message: GSK terminated 110 employees' contracts working at its Chinese subsidiary for "misconduct" allegedly dating back over 18 months, the company said March 6. GSK previously fired five managing executives. Its chief executive, Andrew Witty, took a 46% pay cut in light of a bribery scandal.
link_name: GlaxoSmithKline fires over 100 Chinese employees in bribery scandal
NY Cosmos headed to Cuba, first pro US team to play there in 16 years

status_message:
Apple Watch and MacBook announcement will be here: http://circanews.com/news/apple-watch-wearable-device
