New York City FC ties 1-1 in MLS debut
Niger and Chad forces escalate battle against Boko Haram
Tripoli airport hit with airstrikes in conflict between rival governments
Taiwanese fishing boat with 49 on board missing off Falkland Islands
US gas prices climbed 34 cents in the last month
Chinese police detain 10 women organizing sexual harassment campaign
Chinese minister says ecommerce sites can't be 'lawless heaven'
Protests run into third day after police shooting in Wisconsin capital
Chinese lunar probe completes space docking test
Battles intensify on the outskirts of Tikrit, Iraq

status_message: White's Third Man Records will issue a recording of "My Happiness" and "That's Where Your Heartaches Begin" on April 18, or Record Store Day. It will be released as a 10-inch, 78r.p.m. facsimile. White secretly bought the Elvis songs at a Graceland auction for $300,000.
link_name: Jack White to release covers of Elvis' early songs

status_message: The winning bidder may release the sole copy of the album for free at any time but may only release it commercially for profit in 88 years, according to a "collector's agreement," RZA said March 5. Wu-Tang member Method Man said March 4 that he was unaware of the provisions of the album.
link_name: Wu-Tang auctioning album that can't be sold for 88 years

status_message: Tesla confirmed March 9 that it fired an undisclosed number of employees in China. While spokesperson Gary Tao said it has hired others to "build up a strong and efficient team to respond more quickly to the market," Tao also said Tesla had a net loss of employees.
link_name: Tesla China staff reduced after slow start to sales

status_message: China's exports increased 48.3% year-on-year in February, while imports fell 20.5% year-on-year, leading to a record surplus of $60.6 billion, China said March 8. The growth in exports beat predictions of analysts, some of whom believe weak domestic demand and low commodity prices impacted trade.
link_name: China's trade surplus hit record in February

status_message: The Vatican made public for the first time on March 8 that two rare Michelangelo documents had gone missing years ago. A man recently contacted a cardinal asking for approximately $108,000 for the documents' safe return.
link_name: Vatican receives ransom demand for stolen Michelangelo documents

status_message: "Chappie" took the No. 1 spot at the box office over the March 6-8 weekend, with $13.3 million. "Focus" slipped to No. 2 in its second weekend in theaters, earning $10 million, and "The Second Best Exotic Marigold Hotel" made $8.6 million in its debut to take the No. 3 spot.
link_name: 'Chappie' wins slow weekend box office with $13.3M in debut

status_message: An unwritten policy that banned the use of certain scientific terms went into effect when Florida Gov. Rick Scott took office in 2011 and applied to all official communications, according to the Florida Center for Investigative Reporting in a story published March 8.
link_name: Report: Florida officials ban terms "climate change" and "global warming"

status_message: Authorities said that 22 arrests had been made during the March 7-8 weekend and that police have identified 200 to 300 people involved in the violence. Charges include rioting, arson and unlawful assembly.
link_name: 22 arrests made after mob storms Indian jail and kills rape suspect

status_message: Reebok has unveiled their latest pump sneakers, the ZPump Fusion, which have several differences from the company's original pump shoe from 1989.
link_name: Reebok re-introduces the Pump, with a whole new design

status_message: A rocket attack March 8 on a UN base in Mali killed three people, including one UN peackeeper, and injured 14 others.
link_name: Three killed in rocket attack on UN base in Mali
EU sanctions oil, money middlemen in Syria
Anti-Netanyahu rally in Tel Aviv draws tens of thousands

status_message: The United Nations Security Council on March 6 adopted a resolution condemning chemical weapons including chlorine in Syria.
link_name: UN condemns Syria chlorine attacks, threatens action if used again
Pro-Russian rebels in Ukraine claim all heavy weapons removed from front line

status_message: The Dutch Safety Board said on March 7 that 533 relatives of 151 victims had visited the recovered wreckage of the airplane. The agency said family members were taken to three locations where wreckage is either being stored or examined. "The visits went well," the agency said.
link_name: Dutch authorities say 533 relatives of MH17 victims visited wreckage

status_message: A Canadian special forces soldier, Sgt. Andrew Joseph Doiron, was killed on March 6 by friendly fire coming from Kurdish troops, Canada's Dept. of National Defence said March 7. Three other Canadian soldiers were also injured.
link_name: Canadian soldier killed by friendly fire in Iraq during battle against Islamic State

status_message: Two security screeners and a third person were arrested and charged with allowing methamphetamine to be smuggled through a checkpoint in exchange for money, the FBI said March 6.
link_name: San Francisco airport security screeners arrested for allowing drug smuggling

status_message: According to the Justice Dept., Judge Ronald Brockmeyer used his court to exact harsh penalties and jail time on Ferguson residents who were unable to pay fines totaling only a few hundred dollars, while he himself had federal tax liens filed against him dating back to 2007.
link_name: Ferguson judge singled out in DOJ report owes $170,000 in unpaid taxes

status_message: Anna Durytska, the sole witness to Russian opposition leader Boris Nemtsov's murder, is being heavily guarded after receiving anonymous death threats.
link_name: Witness of Nemtsov killing under police protection in Ukraine after death threats

status_message: Between three and five explosions hit the city of Maiduguri over the course of several hours. Reports indicate that some of the blasts were caused by suicide bombers. Casualty figures varied, but dozens were reported to have died
link_name: Several explosions rock northeastern Nigerian city, dozens killed

status_message: A Palestinian man drove his car into a group of pedestrians near a border police station in Jerusalem on March 6.
link_name: Palestinian man uses car as a weapon during attack in Jerusalem
Larry David's first Broadway play debuts
Convicted Silk Road creator Ross Ulbricht requests new trial

status_message: On March 7 the air pollution film "Under the Dome" was taken down from major streaming video websites in China. However, discussion of the film, which had received tens of millions of more views since March 2 when it passed 100 million views, is reportedly still being allowed on social media sites.
link_name: Documentary on air pollution in China taken down from streaming sites
FDA approves 'biosimilar' rival to Amgen chemotherapy drug
Pentagon says Islamic State militants pushed out of Al Baghdadi
Chinese premier announces reforms at annual legislative meeting
US consumer credit rises 4.2% in January
Dow finishes week down more than 278 points
Schock will implement more protections after reports of lavish spending
Reports: Federal prosecutors to file corruption charges against Sen. Menendez

status_message: The Sandy Hook Advisory Commission report was submitted to Connecticut Gov. Dannel Malloy on March 6. The report marks the end of the panel's two-year investigation and analysis.
link_name: Sandy Hook Advisory Commission delivers final report to CT governor

status_message: The UK's National Crime Agency (NCA) announced 57 arrests on March 6. The suspects were arrested across the UK beginning on March 2, including one man suspected of stealing 400,000 Yahoo email passwords in 2012 and one man suspected of hacking into a U.S. Dept. of Defense network in 2014.
link_name: 57 arrested in UK 'strike week' cybercrime raids
Last Ebola patient in Liberia released from treatment ward
CIA chief announces major reorganization with focus on cyber operations
Five arrested in MyCoin bitcoin fraud probe
Justice Dept. charges three in 'largest data breach' in history

status_message: On March 6, German parliament approved a wide-ranging quota system that will require companies to have at least 30% women on their supervisory boards by 2016, or propose measures to increase the number of women directors in their companies.
link_name: Germany to require companies to have at least 30% women on their supervisory boards

status_message: A study, published March 5, claims that there were at least 46,000 Islamic State supporting Twitter accounts in active use between Sept. 2014 - Dec. 2014. The study also claims about 1,000 of these accounts were suspended by Twitter. Twitter said it suspended more than that but did not give a specific number.
link_name: Study: 46,000 Islamic State Twitter accounts used in 2014

status_message: This gets into a bit of what we have in store for wearables with Circa
link_name: The next stage in the battle for our attention: Our wrists

status_message: Military court approved a motion from Manning's legal team to order the US Army use female pronouns for Chelsea Manning, and preclude her former first name. The order does not apply retroactively.
link_name: Military court orders US Army to refer to Chelsea Manning as a woman

status_message: The Wall Street Journal reported March 6 that Apple will join the Dow Jones Industrial Average later this month, replacing AT&T. Apple is currently traded on the NASDAQ.
link_name: Report: Apple to join Dow Jones Industrial Average

status_message: The FTC announced March 5 that Allstar Marketing Group, which marketed the Snuggie, agreed to pay to settle charges it had mislead customers. It said in a press release that the marketer promised customers buy-one, get-one-free promotions but instead charged higher fees for "processing and handling".
link_name: Snuggie marketing company to pay $8 million fine for misleading advertising

status_message: The U.S. added 295,000 jobs in February, the Labor Dept. reported March 6. Economists had expected the country to add 235,000. The overall unemployment rate fell to 5.5% from 5.7%, beating expectations.
link_name: US unemployment drops to 5.5%

status_message: At least five student protesters were detained by police March 6 in Letpadan, according to the AP. In Yangon, eight protesters detained on March 5 were released.
link_name: Burmese student protesters detained by police

status_message: Alexei Navalny was released March 6 after serving 15 days in jail. He had requested an early release so he could attend the funeral of slain opposition figure Boris Nemtsov, but the request was denied. The March 1 event Navalny was convicted of promoting turned into a march remembering Nemtsov.
link_name: Russian opposition figure Navalny released from jail

status_message: Police on March 6 asked a court to issue a arrest warrant for the accused attacker, 55-year-old Kim Ki-jong. The charges include attempted murder and illegal use of violence against a foreign diplomat. Kim previously received a suspended sentence in 2010 for throwing bricks at Japan's ambassador to South Korea.
link_name: Attempted murder charges sought against accused attacker of US ambassador in South Korea

status_message: Journalists from countries on the United Nations World Heritage Committee will visit the Great Barrier Reef March 14-21 on a trip paid for the Australian government. UNESCO will consider putting the reef on its "in danger" list when it meets in June. The Australian government is lobbying to prevent that.
link_name: Australia lobbying to prevent Great Barrier Reef from being listed as 'in danger'

status_message: Amazon on March 6 launched an online store inside of Alibaba's Tmall shopping site. The Amazon Tmall store sells items from overseas, while Amazon.cn has long been available in China.
link_name: Amazon launches online store on Alibaba shopping website in China

status_message: Officials with the Los Angeles Coroner's Office identified the homeless man as Charley Leundeu Keunang on March 5, and said he was Cameroonian. Officials said he had been living with the stolen identify of a French man, Charley Saturmin Robinet. The real Robinet is "alive and well in France."
link_name: Coroner identifies homeless man shot by LAPD on Skid Row

status_message: The Federal Reserve said March 5 that 31 major banks passed the annual stress test to determine if they are able to continue lending "during a period marked by severe recession and financial market volatility."
link_name: Fed says major US banks pass stress test

status_message: A single-engine, which appeared to be a vintage WWII-era Ryan PT-22 Recruit, crash landed on a golf course near the Santa Monica Municipal Airport near Venice, California. Both NBC News and TMZ reported actor Harrison Ford was the pilot and only person on board. Reports indicate Ford was bloodied after the crash and may have suffered serious injuries.
link_name: Reports: Plane piloted by actor Harrison Ford crash lands, actor injured

status_message: David Cameron, March 5, said he will only take part in one televised debate between the leaders of seven British political parties. Cameron will not take place in a proposed head-to-head with Labour leader Ed Miliband.
link_name: British PM accused of 'ducking' election debates

status_message: On March 5, the Mandarin Oriental Hotel Group confirmed that hackers had improperly accessed guests' credit card data in an "isolated number" of its hotels in Europe and the U.S. The hotel group blamed "undetectable malware" for the breach.
link_name: Mandarin Oriental hotel confirms 'isolated' credit card data breach

status_message: A group called Women on $20s says it wants to "literally raise the profile of a woman in a male-dominated field." The group has launched a petition online.
link_name: Group seeks to put a woman on the $20 dollar bill
Google tops Fortune list of best companies to work for 6th year in a row
Softcard to shut down following Google acquisition

status_message: The Lim family told CNN early on March 5 that Canadian officials have confirmed that Hyeon Soo Lim, 60, is being held by North Korean authorities. Further information on his detention has not been made public.
link_name: Canadian pastor detained in North Korea

status_message: Draft emission limits that go before the EU in March are less than those of China, Japan, and the U.S., according to a Greenpeace report released on March 5. The draft would allow much more pollution because lobbyists steered policy makers away from using the best available pollution-reducing techniques, the report says.
link_name: Greenpeace accuses coal industry of weakening EU draft pollution limits

status_message: On March 5, travel company Uri Tours said the ban on foreign runners for the April Pyongyang marathon had been lifted. North Korea lifted its Ebola travel ban on March 2. Travel agencies said flights were permitted.
link_name: North Korea lifts Ebola ban, foreign runners to compete in marathon

status_message: The Aqueduct Global Flood Risk Country Rankings released on March 5 ranks 163 countries (by current annual average population) affected by river floods. The WRI compiled the list with its Aqueduct Global Flood Analyzer. Population growth and climate change are exacerbating the impact of floods, the WRI says.
link_name: Millions in southeast Asia affected by river flooding, report says

status_message: DreamWorks Animation CFO Fazal Merchant said March 4 that the company is looking to "Kung Fu Panda 3" and to licensing deals with Netflix to help turn the company around. "Kung Fu Panda 3" is being developed by Oriental DreamWorks, which is a joint-venture in China. The movie has a 2016 release date.
link_name: DreamWorks Animation looking to China, Netflix, to save company
Hillary Clinton says she 'asked State to release' all emails
Oldest living person turns 117
AbbVie buys cancer drug maker for $21 billion
China sets GDP growth rate at 7% for 2015, lowest in over a decade
Lawmakers call for investigation into federal approval of highway safety devices
Hobbled Seattle tunneling machine in position for repairs
Craft marketplace Etsy files for $100 million IPO
Improved SoCal air quality is helping children's lungs, study finds
EA shuts down main studio of 'SimCity' developer Maxis
US ambassador to South Korea hospitalized after attack
Silicon Valley $415 million poaching settlement gets preliminary approval
Eurozone retail sales grew at fastest rate since 2005 in January
Superbug outbreak extends to second Calif. hospital
Microsoft to bring 'cross-buy' to Windows 10, Xbox One games
France's highest court approves extradition of Kazakh oligarch

status_message: Anonymous hacktivist Matt DeHart was extradited by Canada on March 1, after a failed bid to secure political asylum. The alleged hacker had fled to Canada with his parents in 2010 after being charged with child pornography offenses. DeHart and his supporters claim the charges were fabricated in order to investigate his links to Anonymous and WikiLeaks.
link_name: Alleged Wikileaks courier Matt DeHart extradited by Canada

status_message: Report: HBO and Apple are in talks to make Apple TV a launch platform for the upcoming standalone streaming service
link_name: HBO in talks with Apple to launch standalone service

status_message: Finance authorities in Naples have opened an investigation into the possible improper use of millions of dollars in restoration funds for Pompeii. Authorities seized $6.4 million in assets from an official overseeing the restoration as a precautionary measure. Authorities are also questioning other officials.
link_name: Italian authorities investigate improper spending of Pompeii restoration funds

status_message:
Court stays lawsuit against Comcast for automatically turning customers' routers into Wi-Fi hotspots 

On March 3, a federal judge in the Northern District of California stayed the lawsuit against Comcast because the two plaintiffs had agreed to resolve all disputes against the company in arbitration rather than through the court system. The two plaintiffs' service agreements with Comcast included an arbitration clause that the court said was valid.
link_name: Court stays lawsuit against Comcast for automatically turning customers' routers into Wi-Fi hotspots
Justice Dept. will not file charges against officer in Ferguson shooting

status_message: The tribunal on March 3 brought charges against Meas Muth, the ex-chief of the navy, who is accused of sending 14,000 people to their deaths. It also charged Buddhist nun Im Chaem, who is accused of running a labor camp. Both were charged with crimes against humanity and murder. They haven't been detained yet.
link_name: Cambodia's Khmer Rouge tribunal charges two more people

status_message: Ebola has orphaned more than 12,000 children in Sierra Leone, according to the Ebola Orphan Report released March 4 by the British charity Street Child. The charity conducted a survey in all 14 districts of Sierra Leone between Jan. 13 and Jan. 27. The average age of orphans is nine years old.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Japan's transport ministry has ordered Uber stop a pilot program in Fukuoka. It said Uber's drivers are not licensed for providing rides. Uber says it is reviewing the program, which is aims to collect transport data on the city. The program is separate from the company's main Japan operations.
link_name: Japan orders Uber to halt urban pilot program

status_message: National People's Congress spokeswoman Fu Ying said March 4 that China will increase its official military budget by "about 10%" in 2015, with solid figures coming out the following day. The increase comes despite slowing GDP growth. The official public budget is thought to be lower than what China actually spends on its military.
link_name: China's military budget to increase by 'about 10%' in 2015

status_message: The Taiwan Investment Commission ruled on March 3 that Alibaba's company structure breached trade rules as a mainland China-based company. The commission gave the e-commerce giant six months to leave Taiwan. Chairman Jack Ma agreed to cooperate and withdraw from the market, MarketWatch reported.
link_name: Taiwan tells China's Alibaba e-commerce giant to leave

status_message: Police on March 4 arrested up to 150 asylum seekers protesting outside a police station against the detention of fellow asylum seekers who were arrested for protesting poor living conditions, refugee advocates said. Nauru's director of police warned protesters would continue to be arrested if they didn't disperse on command.
link_name: Nauru police arrest several dozen asylum seekers protesting detentions

status_message: Nvidia on March 3 demoed the Shield console based on Android TV that will go on sale in May for $199, including one controller. The device features Nvidia's new Tegra X1 processor. It can stream 1080p video games and 4K video.
link_name: Nvidia Shield set-top gaming system to cost $199
Alabama high court orders probate judges to stop issuing marriage licenses to same-sex couples
Target to cut $2 billion in costs over 2 years
French President Hollande to visit Cuba
HBO Go app released for PS4
President of Namibia wins $5 million prize for African leadership
Apple overtakes Samsung in 2014 smartphones sales
GM and Chrysler see sales rise in February, Ford slips
Congress passes 'clean' Homeland Security funding bill
Parents of obese children in Puerto Rico may face fines
Colorado sold 66 tons of marijuana in 2014
Second Pebble Kickstarter breaks record for most money raised
Edward Snowden working with American, German lawyers to return home
Boehner says House will take up 'clean' Homeland Security funding bill
Europe seeks US, China partnerships to develop 5G wireless technology

status_message: Hikers can no longer dig holes in the snow to use as toilets at four camps around the summit, Nepalese authorities said March 3. More than 700 climbers and guides spend two months around Everest during climbing season. The large amounts of feces and urine are health hazards. Waste at base camp is disposed properly.
link_name: Nepal bans toilet holes on parts of Mt. Everest's summit

status_message: The 9,350-foot-high Villarrica volcano erupted overnight March 3. Authorities raised the volcano alert day earlier. More than 3,000 people evacuated as a precaution. The area is a popular tourist spot. No reports of injuries or damage have been reported.
link_name: Volcano in Chile erupts, evacuations ordered

status_message: Macau gambling revenue fell 48.6% in February year-over-year, a record decrease, to $2.4 billion. The decrease, the ninth straight monthly drop, was slightly less severe than analysts expected, however, causing shares in Macau casinos to tick up March 3. Revenue in Feb. 2014 had increased 40% year-over-year.
link_name: Macau gambling revenue nearly falls in half in February

status_message: Hundreds of thousands of Europeans will die prematurely over the next two decades due to air pollution, the European Environment Agency (EEA) said in its 2015 State and Outlook report released March 2. It calls on governments to act on the issue.
link_name: EU agency warns pollution will cause many premature deaths

status_message: Abe admitted on March 3 that his party received potentially improper donations of Y620,000 ($5,170) from two companies that had received government subsidies in 2012 and 2013. Subsidized companies are barred from making political donations for a year after receiving funds.
link_name: Japan's PM Shinzo Abe accused of financial impropriety

status_message: Hillary Clinton did not have a government email address and used her personal account to conduct business as secretary of state, State Dept. officials told the NY Times March 2. Federal officials' emails are considered government records that legally need to be preserved with some exemptions for sensitive materials.
link_name: Hillary Clinton used private email address as Sec. of State

status_message: The families of three victims filed a federal wrongful death lawsuit March 2 against Santa Barbara County and the Sheriff's Dept., as well as against the owners of the apartment where two of the students were roommates with the young man that stabbed them to death.
link_name: Parents of Isla Vista shooting spree victims file wrongful death lawsuit
Maersk wants 11 more of the world's largest freighters
Superintendent at center of Atlanta cheating scandal dies of cancer
Costco names Visa and Citi as new credit partners
Islamic State threatens Twitter over deleted accounts
Nasdaq breaks 5,000 for first time since dot-com bubble
Supreme Court hears contentious Arizona redistricting case
New York City reverses public school cell phone ban

status_message: Tinder on March 2 launched Tinder Plus, a premium tier that lets users "like" an unlimited number of profiles and search for matches outside of their geographic location. The service costs $19.99 per month for people in the U.S. older than 30 and $9.99 per month for people younger than 30.
link_name: Tinder debuts paid tier in the US
Whitney Plantation becomes first slavery museum in the US
California Republicans formally recognize gay GOP group
Family of friend of Boston bombing suspect killed by FBI to sue for $30 million
Nearly 100,000 UK children affected by benefits cuts, report finds
Sen. Barbara Mikulski, longest-serving woman in Congress, won't seek reelection
HTC addresses camera complaints with One M9
Toronto police say 'mystery tunnel' case closed, no threat to public

status_message: Australian officials told Reuters March 1 that the search may be called off if the plane is not found by the end of the current search mission. It would need significant international financial aid to continue.
link_name: MH370 search would need new funds to continue after current stage, Australia says

status_message: A group of LAPD officers responding to a robbery report wrestled a man to the ground and used a Taser on him. They eventually shot and killed the man as he was on the ground. The LAPD said the man was struggling over an officer's weapon.
link_name: Fatal shooting by police in Los Angeles' Skid Row caught on video

status_message: By March 2, "Under the Dome," a documentary about air pollution in China, was watched more than 100 million times on Chinese online streaming sites in its first two days of release. "There's no way to avoid" breathing pollution, says filmmaker Chai Jing, a former Chinese Central Television reporter.
link_name: Documentary on air pollution in China takes Chinese Internet by storm

status_message: A SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket successfully launched on schedule on March 1 from Cape Canaveral,  carrying a pair of communication satellites built by Boeing in orbit.
link_name: SpaceX successfully launches satellites

status_message: The Mexican government  announced it will ban gillnets in 5,000 square miles of the northern Gulf of California for two years beginning in March.
link_name: Mexico rolls out plan to save endangered vaquita, world's smallest porpoise
Black hole with weight of 12 billion suns surprises astronomers

status_message: Nina Pham plans to file a lawsuit March 2 against Texas Health Resources, the parent company of Texas Health Presbyterian Hospital Dallas where she became infected with Ebola in the fall of 2014.
link_name: Nurse to sue Dallas hospital over Ebola contraction

status_message: In its opening weekend Feb. 27-March 1, the con artist film "Focus," starring Will Smith and Margot Robbie, pulled in $19.1 million, enough to take the top spot for the weekend's box office but lower than other recent films starring Will Smith.
link_name: 'Focus' tops box office over slow weekend

status_message: Saturday Night Live aired a skit Feb. 28 parodying a Toyota Super Bowl commercial and drew ire on social media. SNL cast member Taran Killam played a father dropping off his daughter, host Dakota Johnson, to join the Islamic State.
link_name: SNL Islamic State skit with Dakota Johnson draws criticism

status_message: Minnie Minoso died in Chicago on March 1 from a heart ailment at the age of either 89 or 90. Baseball's first black Latino player debuted for the Cleveland Indians in 1949 before being traded to the Chicago White Sox in 1951 where he became a fan favorite and had his No. 9 retired by the team in 1983.
link_name: Minnie Minoso, first black Latin American MLB player, dies

status_message: Iran's deputy telecommunications and IT minister told the Fars news agency March 1 that Iran will welcome Google and other internet services companies. He said the government was willing to assist in establishing local facilities.
link_name: Iran ready to welcome Google if it observes cultural rules

status_message: Thousands of Russians marched in Moscow on March 1. The protest was originally supposed to feature Nemtsov and criticize Russia's actions in Ukraine. After his death two days prior, the march turned into a memorial for the Putin critic.
link_name: Thousands march in Moscow in honor of slain Putin critic
